<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Use Rises in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- More Canadians are hooking their
home computers up to the Internet, a new survey said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The study of 2,013 Canadians in late March and early April
indicated 20 percent of households had access to the Internet, a
sharp rise from 13 percent in a similar survey last November.
</P>
<P>
The new figures confirmed earlier findings of the demographics
of Internet users: predominantly males aged 18 to 29 and 45 to 59.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the spread of personal computers in the
country is not growing nearly as fast.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows 40 percent of Canadian households own
computers, a slight increase from the 36 percent level indicated
by the statistics agency last year.
</P>
<P>
It also found that most computer owners earn more than 24,000
U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by Environics Research Group Inc., is
considered to have a margin of error of plus or minus 2.2
percentage points, 19 times out of 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
