<HEADLINE> Britain Welcomes Lifting of EU Ban on Ulster Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Labor government Wednesday
welcomed the European Union's (EU) decision to lift a two-year-old
ban on Northern Ireland's beef exports from June 1.
</P>
<P>
The EU's executive Commission announced early Wednesday that it
was exempting Britain's Northern Ireland region from a worldwide
ban on British beef exports because Northern Ireland has kept
detailed computerized records for years.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the easing of beef ban, British Agriculture
Minister Jack Cunningham said in a statement issued early
Wednesday, "This is excellent news and an important day for the
United Kingdom's beef industry."
</P>
<P>
Cunningham stressed that the British government is to make
"sustained efforts to win a wider lifting of the ban to benefit
exporters throughout the United Kingdom."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ben Gill, president of Britain's National Farmers'
Union, said that the EU decision would boost confidence and
increase the impetus for a lifting of the ban nationwide.
</P>
<P>
"This is fantastic news and we are confident that in the near
future we will also be celebrating the resumption of beef exports
from England and Wales," Gill said.
</P>
<P>
The EU Commission decided to impose a worldwide ban on British
beef exports in March 1996 when Britain's previous Conservative
government admitted possible links between mad cow disease and its
human equivalent Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
