<HEADLINE> European Food Safety Legislation Update Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 27 (Xinhua) -- An official of the U.N. food
agency has urged European countries to revise and update their
legislation governing food safety, according to the U.N.
Department of Public Information here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some European food exports have been rejected because of their
contamination with pathogenic bacteria such as Salmonella and
failure to meet safety regulations for certain canned foods, John
Lupien, director of the FAO Nutrition Division, was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Other reasons for their rejection include non-permitted food
additives, incorrect Labeling, filth, pesticide residues, banned
pesticides, heavy metal contamination and faulty packaging, Lupien
told a FAO regional conference in Europe Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Citing statistics from the United States Food and Drug
Administration, Lupien said some 770 shipments of European food
products, including cheeses, vegetables, fruits, spices, baked
foods, tea, coffee, mushrooms, soups and fish, were rejected by
the U.S. early this year.
</P>
<P>
The FAO, or the Food and Agriculture Organization, estimated
that the international food trade has grown to over 400 billion
U.S. dollars a year and is expected to go up further. Europe is
one of the largest food exporters in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
