<HEADLINE> France to Hold Exhibition of Napoleon's Invasion of Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 27 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition opens Friday on
Napoleon Bonaparte's invasion of Egypt from 1798 to 1801 at the
Army Museum in Paris, reported Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
On display will be a manuscript of a decree signed by Napoleon
ordering all Egyptians to wear a cockade of the French Republic's
tricolor flag, which was put on the walls of Cairo and Alexandria
by French troops at that time.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, named "The Campaign of Egypt, Myths and
Realities," will also display 133 other objects including a
telescope used by Napoleon during the Battle of Pyramids, French
army uniforms and arms of honor, and weapons such as sabers and
yataghans used by the Turkish-Egyptian troops.
</P>
<P>
The Egypt Campaign confirmed the military genius of Napoleon,
although it remained highly controversial whether it was a
military success.
</P>
<P>
Some 38,000 French troops were stuck in Egypt and other parts
of the Middle East for three years before they could re-embark on
ships to return to France, because the route home in the
Mediterranean was cut by their enemies, the British.
</P>
<P>
One third of the French expedition force died, half of them of
contagious diseases, as stated in the documents of military
hospitals to be displayed.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition coincides with another on the ancient maritime
civilization of Alexandria which was inaugurated last week by
President Jacques Chirac and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak at
the Petit Palais in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Both France and Egypt are marking the bicentenary of the Egypt
Campaign, which they regard as the beginning of the relationship
between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
