<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Has Poor Record of Forest Conservation in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Britain has a poor record of forest
conservation in Europe as it comes fourth from the bottom in a
survey of 15 European countries, according to a report Wednesday
by the World Wide Fund for Nature.
</P>
<P>
The first ever detailed survey on forestry management showed
that virtually no natural forests are left in Britain, which ranks
12th out of the 15 countries assessed by the survey.
</P>
<P>
"The UK has virtually no natural forests left, and some
ecosystem types have entirely disappeared. Forest cover is low and
most British `forests' are actually plantations," said the report.
</P>
<P>
The fund said that about half of the country's ancient forests
have been lost in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, despite widespread forest loss, only 2.5 percent of
the remaining area is under strict protection, it added.
</P>
<P>
The survey gave each country a scorecard based on scores in
several categories including levels of pollution, the amount of
protected forest area, the standards of production and the
national environmental, social and cultural policies applied to
forests.
</P>
<P>
Britain ranks behind Finland, Austria, Greece, Sweden, Turkey,
France, Norway, Germany, Italy and the Netherlands. Only Spain,
Belgium and Denmark have worse records than Britain. Switzerland
emerged top. 
</P>
</TEXT>
