<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Mobilize 1,000 Soldiers at Football World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 27 (Xinhua) -- France will mobilize 1,000 soldiers
to guard airports, railway stations, sea ports and other places
frequented by the public during the 1998 France Football World Cup
finals, announced the French Interior Ministry Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The mobilization makes up a reinforcement of the Vigipirate
anti-terrorist operation renewed by France since 1995, as the
1,000 soldiers will join 860 of their fellow soldiers already
mobilized over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers will be deployed in the sensitive points of the 10
departments where the World Cup finals will be held from June 10
to July 12, as well as in the areas which serve as traveling
transitions for the supporters and spectators of the matches, said
the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The department of Seine-et-Marne near Paris, the only
department which will receive five national football teams from
Brazil, Mexico, Saudi Arabia, Austria and Belgium, will have an
extra strong deployment of soldiers and police.
</P>
<P>
Each national team joining the matches will have close
protection by the elite RAID police or the EPIGN air-borne
gendarmery, whose deployment will be arranged by the private
security companies in charge of security during the World Cup by
the organizers.
</P>
<P>
The Comite Francais d'Organisation (CFO) has sent at least 48
million francs (8 million U.S. dollars) to the Interior Ministry
to "compensate for the extra cost linked to the security during
the World Cup," Agence France-Presse quoted police union sources
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the CFO has mobilized 5,000 volunteers to work as
security agents with 1,850 professionals.
</P>
<P>
The Vigipirate anti-terrorist operation has been put into force
twice since its creation in 1978.
</P>
<P>
The first such operation was launched in January 1991 at the
outbreak of the Gulf War, while the second was launched in
September 1995 following a car bomb attack on a Jewish school in
southern France.
</P>
<P>
French Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement said Tuesday
that the new mobilization was not the outcome of high
psychological tension, but was aimed at securing the World Cup
finals.
</P>
<P>
French police Tuesday launched a simultaneous raid with their
German, Swiss, Belgian and Italian counterparts on suspected
sympathizers of the Algerian terrorist Armed Islamic Group, making
an unspecified number of arrests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
