<HEADLINE> Kyrgyzstan Enjoys Healthy Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Kyrgyzstan President Askar Akayev
said Wednesday that his country's gross domestic product (GDP) in
1997 grew by 10 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Akayev disclosed the figure at an international conference held
in the Kyrgyz capital, Alma Ata, to mark the fifth anniversary of
the issuance of the Kyrgyz currency, the Som.
</P>
<P>
Akayev attributed the country's economic growth mainly to the
issuance of Som and the assistance provided by the world
community, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in particular.
</P>
<P>
The Kyrgyz people had mastered their national economy since the
issuance of Som in May 1993, which was also a strong catalyst for
economic reform, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the country's budget deficit dropped
from 25 percent to 5 percent, he noted. The inflation rate also
declined from 1366 percent to 14.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the economic recovery in the past two years, the Som
maintained a value of 18.85 against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Michel Camdessus, managing director of the IMF, said in his
speech at the conference that Kyrgyzstan had begun to benefit from
the introduction of market economy.
</P>
<P>
Now the country had to make great efforts to take advantage of
the economic globalization to further develop its economy, he
pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
