<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Government Plans to Halve Gold Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The federal government approved
Wednesday a plan to halve its gold reserves but it still requires
the approval first from the parliament and then from the people
through a referendum.
</P>
<P>
If endorsed, the legislation will allow the Swiss National Bank
to sell about 1,300 tons of gold, or half of its current 2,590-ton
gold reserves, according to reports from the Swiss capital of
Berne.
</P>
<P>
After the plan was approved Wednesday by the cabinet, Swiss
Finance Minister Kaspar Villiger told reporters that he hoped the
parliament would pass the plan by the end of this year and that a
referendum could follow in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
Villiger said that Switzerland could not start selling half of
its gold reserves before late or early 2000.
</P>
<P>
To avoid disrupting prices on world gold markets, Villiger
said, the selling of roughly half of Switzerland's gold reserves
would probably be spread over five to seven years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
