<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenhouse Gas Emissions Rise in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Canada's greenhouse gases emissions
have continued to rise despite promised reductions.
</P>
<P>
Canada has promised to stabilize its emissions of greenhouse
gases at 1990 levels by the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
But on average, Canada produced 1.5 percent more carbon
dioxide, the most powerful greenhouse gas, each year from 1985 to
1994, new figures showed.
</P>
<P>
The country's emissions of carbon dioxide climbed 3.8 percent
in 1995, the latest year for which verified figures are available.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Canadians have been producing still more of the
pollutant gases each year, even though precise amounts are not
available.
</P>
<P>
At the current rate, Canadian greenhouse emissions will grow 11
percent from 1990 to 2000, said Commissioner of the Environment
and Sustainable Development Brian Emmett in a report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"What really concerns me is that far too often, the government
is not keeping the promises it makes both to Canadians and to the
world," Emmett said.
</P>
<P>
"If the performance of the government does not improve, the
environment and the health of Canadians will be damaged," he
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
