<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costs to Cope With EMU Forecast to Rise for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The costs of adapting the
information technology systems of European companies to cope with
the European economic and monetary union (EMU) are estimated to
rise to 150-400 billion U.S. dollars, the Financial Times reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Citing a research by the information technology consultancy
Gartner Group, the newspaper said that over a seven-year period to
2003, the cost of preparing European companies' information
technology systems to deal with EMU could exceed some estimates of
the cost of dealing with the millennium bug of the computer
system.
</P>
<P>
"We recently revised our estimates for the overall European
cost of EMU to include alternative scenarios, increasing staff
costs and more information from early EMU projects," the
consultancy said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the research said that unfortunately, EMU and the
millennium bug projects partially overlap in Europe and as a
result, many companies will be left with little spare spending to
invest in new information technology systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
