<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Ready to Oppose NATO Eastward Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Russia is ready to take appropriate
measures against the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's (NATO)
eastward expansion, the Russian Defense Ministry stated on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an article published by the Nezavisimaya Gazeta, Colonel
General Leonid Ivashov, head of the Defense Ministry's main
department for international military cooperation, denied that
Moscow had reconciled itself to the alliance's enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Ivashov said if former Soviet republics become candidates for
NATO membership, Russia would have to increase its strategic forces
in the northwest of the country.
</P>
<P>
Russia might also have to reduce its commitments regarding
tactical and strategic weapons, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Response measures may vary, but Russia's security will be
ensured," he added.
</P>
<P>
"At all official levels we openly say that if former Soviet
republics become candidates for admission into the alliance, the
situation in Europe will become unstable and the geopolitical
situation will change," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ivashov criticized NATO for failing to discuss serious issues
during the first meeting of the Russia-NATO Joint Permanent
Council.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia was extremely concerned over the transparency of
the development of NATO's military infrastructure, especially in
the territories of new Eastern European members of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
As NATO was moving closer to Russia's borders, it should
take note of Russia's national security, Ivashov said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
