<HEADLINE> Indian Government Comes Under Fire On Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government led by the
Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) came under fire Wednesday in Lok
Sabha, the Lower House of Parliament, for its decision to conduct
nuclear tests earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Virtually the entire opposition accused the BJP-led coalition
of starting a nuclear arms race in the Indian Sub-continent.
</P>
<P>
They questioned the need and the timing of the tests, saying
there was no threat from China, and cautioned against the danger
of inducting nuclear weapons for deployment.
</P>
<P>
Congress said irresponsible statements by some cabinet
ministers had damaged India's relations with many countries
including China and Pakistan and lambasted the government for not
generating a national consensus before exercising the nuclear
option.
</P>
<P>
Indrajit Gupta, leader of the Communist Party of India, asked
the Vajpayee government to explain the "sudden provocation" for
carrying out the nuclear tests and warned it could trigger a
nuclear arms race in the region.
</P>
<P>
Former minister of state for external affairs Salman Khurshid
accused the Vajpayee government of reversing the peaceful nuclear
policy laid down by the country's first Prime Minister Jawaharlal
Nehru.
</P>
<P>
When Nehru set up the Atomic Energy Commission, he explicitly
said India's nuclear policy would be peaceful and create energy to
build a self-reliant economy, Khurshid said Wednesday at a
function to mark Nehru's 34th death anniversary.
</P>
<P>
The heated debate also saw the opposition charging the ruling
BJP with trying to derive political mileage out of the tests.
</P>
<P>
The debate on nuclear will continue Thursday and Vajpayee will
answer questions raised by the opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
