<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> An Exclusive Interview with U.S. Experts on China Daniel  Burstein and Arne De Keijzer  by Zhou Xisheng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Prominent American experts on
China told Xinhua in an exclusive interview Wednesday that the
United States and China should cooperate rather than clash in
handling issues concerning bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"American politicians and strategists should make objective
assessments and analysis of China's role in the world, and the
United States should adopt a policy of 'dynamic engagement'
towards China," said Daniel Burstein and Arne De Keijzer, American
experts on China and the authors of the newly published monograph
entitled "Big Dragon."
</P>
<P>
The two authors made the remarks at the headquarters of the
Blackstone Group, a leading private investment bank based in New
York.
</P>
<P>
Burstein, a senior advisor of the Blackstone Group, and De
Keijzer, who served on the staff of the National Committee on
United States-China Relations earlier in his career and is now
head of his own consulting firm, said that "Big Dragon" has caught
so many Americans' attention that some U.S. Congressmen have
expressed their willingness to promote the book worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Burstein said he and De Keijzer made their first trip to China
in the early 1970s and have returned dozens of times. They have
met numerous Chinese government officials, scholars and economy
and trade leaders. It is their informed perspective and
cross-culture experience which shaped "Big Dragon."
</P>
<P>
Burstein said that there are sharp differences between "Big
Dragon" and the book "The Coming Conflict Between the United
States and China" published last year. The former is shaped by
their on-the-spot investigation and observation of China in past
decades while the latter is based on the hearsay and conjecture of
a few American newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The so-called "China Threat" is radical and unfair, which does
not reflect the reality of China and the development trend of the
Sino-U.S. relations, said Burstein, adding that China's democratic
process and modern construction are moving forward. China has
been becoming an even more responsible member of the international
community, a trend conducive to the further development of the
Sino-U.S. relations rather than prompting conflicts between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
De Keijzer, for his part, maintained that American politicians
and strategists should objectively assess and analyze the positive
changes taking place in China since it adopted the policy of
reform and opening to the outside world in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Holding that the United States should pursue a policy of
"dynamic engagement" towards China, De Keijzer said China has
undergone great changes in recent decades with enhanced
comprehensive national strength. The United States should regard
China's development as a challenge to its creativity and
innovation rather than a political, military and economic threat.
</P>
<P>
This challenge would contribute not only to the progress of the
United States, but also to world peace and prosperity, said de
Keijzer, and the best response from the United States to this
challenge was to adopt a policy of full engagement towards China.
</P>
<P>
De Keijzer also warned that while adopting the "dynamic
engagement" policy towards China, the United States cannot impose
its one-sided thinking on China, such as setting up preconditions
in granting the most favored nation trade status to China as well
as in the issue of human rights.
</P>
<P>
The United States should conduct patient, sincere and true
dialogue with China, and take full advantage of the opportunities
looming from China's development in the areas of economy and
trade, culture, education, technology, environment and energy,
said De Keijzer.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should also improve their cooperation both in
the international and regional organizations, he added.
</P>
<P>
In conclusion, Burstein and De Keijzer said President Clinton's
visit to China stands foremost among the 18 recommendations made
in "Big Dragon," and they hoped that Clinton's forthcoming visit
was a success.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-27 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Announces Ambitious Plan to Transfer Caspian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Wednesday announced an
ambitious plan of exporting the Caspian Sea oil through Iranian
territory instead of other routes, dealing a new blow to the shaky
U.S. d'Amato sanction law against Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Oil Minister Ali Majedi said that Iran has planned to
transfer oil of the Caspian Sea littoral states in three stages,
saying that the first stage would be laying a new pipeline from
the world largest inland sea to the Iranian capital Tehran.
</P>
<P>
By laying a 392-kilometer pipeline from the Caspian port of
Neka in Mazadaran province to Tehran, the official news agency
IRNA quoted him as saying, the Caspian oil will be transferred to
two Iranian refineries in Tehran and Tabriz to swap with Iranian
oil in the Persian Gulf terminals.
</P>
<P>
Majedi said that the first-phase project would be put to the
international tenders next week at a seminar in London, adding
that the stage was estimated to cost 400 million U.S. dollars,
which would be paid from the sale of the crude oil in swap deal.
</P>
<P>
The project will be completed within two years and it will take
five years to pay off the cost, he said, adding that the pipeline
would carry oil from Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan and Turkmenistan to
Tehran and Tabriz refineries and the same amount of crude would be
delivered in the Persian Gulf terminals to the international
customers.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official put the capacity of the pipeline at
40,000 barrels per day (bpd), saying that the capacity was not
sufficient to meet the demand of the contracts already signed on
the swap deal with the Caspian states.
</P>
<P>
The second stage is to transfer the Caspian oil to two other
Iranian refineries in Isfahan and Arak, central Iran, Majedi said,
and the third one is to pipe the Caspian oil to the Kharg terminal
in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian plan was announced after the U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright warned foreign companies that Washington
remained strong opposition to oil and gas pipelines through Iran
to transfer the Caspian oil.
</P>
<P>
Washington will carefully examine and take appropriate measures
under the Iran-Libya Sanction Act adopted in 1996, better known as
the d'Amato law, she said last week.
</P>
<P>
She made the remark after U.S. President Bill Clinton announced
to waiver threats against foreign firms helping Iran to develop
offshore gas field, under a strong pressure from the European
states.
</P>
<P>
However, reports said that Anglo-Dutch Shell was currently
carrying out a feasibility study of various pipelines through
Iran and the study might be completed by autumn. Some other
foreign companies, including the U.S. Mobil, also intended to be
involved in Iranian projects.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the Iranian new plan would deal a serious
challenge to the d'Amato law, which bans foreign company to put
more than 20 million dollars investment in the energy sector of
Iran and Libya as a punitive measure against the two countries'
alleged support to terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
