<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Crop Elimination High on U.N. Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Eliminating illegal drug
crops is one of the core issues to be dealt with at the special
session of the U.N. General Assembly on the world drug problem to
be held here on June 8-10.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. International Drug Control Program
(UNDCP), the global acreage for coca and opium cultivation totals
over half the size of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
About 90 percent of the world's opium poppy is grown in
Afghanistan and Myanmar, and most of the world's coca crop is
cultivated in Bolivia, Colombia and Peru, the UNDCP said.
</P>
<P>
The coca bush and the opium poppy are the basis of the highly
addictive drugs cocaine and heroin, which are abused by some 21
million people globally.
</P>
<P>
However, in villages around the world, a rising number of
peasant farmers are turning away from drug corps due to falling
prices and government pressure.
</P>
<P>
In most cases, the prices paid to farmers for coca leaf and
opium poppy are no longer as attractive as they were, said Pino
Arlacchi, executive director of the UNDCP.
</P>
<P>
In countries where the alternative development program is
practiced, projects are designed with community input to help
farmers increase yields, market products, generate additional
income and raise living standards.
</P>
<P>
UNDCP figures show that projects introduced over the last
decade have led to a decline in drug crop cultivation in a number
of countries, with an elimination in Pakistan and Thailand and a
cut of 40 percent in coca cultivation in Peru.
</P>
<P>
Government leaders are expected to adopt a political
declaration committing themselves to eliminating or substantially
reducing illicit drug cultivation by 2008 at the special session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
