<HEADLINE> Cyprus Stresses Position on Sovereignty Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus stressed on Wednesday that
any settlement of the protracted Cyprus problem should be based on
a single sovereignty as provided for in a United Nations Security
Council resolution.
</P>
<P>
"The government (of Cyprus) considers paragraph two of the
U.N. Security Council Resolution 939 as the cornerstone of a
Cyprus solution," government spokesman Christos Stylianides told
reporters after a cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
The 1994 resolution maintains that a solution to the Cyprus
issue "must be based on a state of Cyprus with a single
sovereignty and international personality and a single
citizenship, with its independence and territorial integrity
safeguarded."
</P>
<P>
Stylianides made the remarks in response to a statement by
Thomas Miller, United States special coordinator for Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Miller told a business conference in Nicosia on Tuesday that
the situation in Cyprus could get worse before getting better and
hinted that the issue of sovereignty may well be on the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
"As far as the government is concerned, there is no issue of
sovereignty to negotiate," Stylianides said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Miller's view that things could get worse, the
spokesman said the Cypriot government is handling the situation in
a responsible manner to avert anything.
</P>
<P>
"The government does not consider that we are going through a
period when unpleasant developments for the people of Cyprus
could occur," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the Mediterranean
island after a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union
with Greece. Turkish Cypriots later set up a breakaway republic in
northern Cyprus which is only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-led efforts to help reunify the island in a bizonal
and bicommunal formula have so far failed to achieve tangible
results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0030 </DOCNO>
