<HEADLINE> German Domestic Demand Picks Up, Institute Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The German economy has begun to profit
from a recovery in domestic demand thanks both to increased
investments and gradually reviving private consumption, a leading
German economic research institute said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
While foreign orders for German investment goods continued to
pour in at "extremely high levels," domestic spending on
investment goods also registered a strong recovery after a
prolonged recession, the Berlin-based German Institute for
Economic Research DIW said.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 1998, Germany's investment goods
industry registered an overall growth of 5 percent in orders, the
institute said.
</P>
<P>
Although private consumption still remained sluggish at the
moment, a revival was expected to come during the course of the
year, the institute predicted. Meanwhile, it saw signs of an
improvement in the construction sector.
</P>
<P>
The latest monthly economic report of the DIW also noted that
the positive development on the domestic market came at a time
when the country's dynamic export expansion had appeared to slow
down slightly for the moment.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, exports would continue to be the main driving
force behind Germany's economic growth in 1998, the DIW said.
</P>
</TEXT>
