<HEADLINE> Demirel: India's Nuke Tests Threaten World Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
on Wednesday expressed his great concern over the nuclear tests
conducted by India earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif, Demirel said the nuclear tests in India not only threaten
stability in south Asia, but also hit a blow to international
peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The president told Sharif that he had conveyed his concern
about the nuclear tests to the Indian government.
</P>
<P>
Demirel stated that Turkey has appreciated the calm and
responsible attitude of Pakistan against this threat, saying that
the Pakistani attitude will produce favorable consequences.
</P>
<P>
Demirel said he believes the international society should
extend further support to Pakistan, which is under threat, and
Turkey will make efforts to this end.
</P>
<P>
On May 11 and 13, India conducted a total of five underground
nuclear tests, which triggered off widespread concern and
international condemnation.
</P>
<P>
India has so far refused to sign the Nuclear Non-proliferation
Treaty and the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, calling them
discriminatory. 
</P>
