<HEADLINE> Most Ports in Greece Remain Closed due Workers' Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Most ports in Greece remained closed
Wednesday as dock workers began a 48-hour strike to protest the
Greek government's plans to privatize the port authorities of
Piraeus and Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
The strike was called by the General Confederation of Greek
Labor and the civil servants' Supreme Administrative Council.
</P>
<P>
In Piraeus, some 15 km southwest of Athens, tension rose when
riot police arrested a trade union leader and another striker.
</P>
<P>
Strikers rushed to the police station and demanded and secured
the release of both men.
</P>
<P>
In the capital city of Athens, police used tear gas to disperse
strikers who tried to break through a cordon and enter the
Parliament building.
</P>
<P>
In the clashes between riot police and strikers, one policeman
was reportedly injured and at least 10 strikers and bystanders
fainted.
</P>
<P>
The clashes also created traffic chaos in downtown Athens.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government denounced the violence in Piraeus and
Athens and reiterated its determination to privatize the two
ports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
