<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Institute Sees Reviving Domestic Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The German economy has begun to profit
from a recovery in domestic demand thanks both to increased
investments and gradually reviving private consumption, a leading
German economic research institute said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
While foreign orders for German investment goods continued to pour
in at "extremely high levels," domestic spendings on investment goods
also registered a strong recovery after a prolonged recession, the
Berlin-based German Institute for Economic Research DIW said.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 1998, Germany's investment goods industry
registered an overall growth of five percent in orders, the institute
said.
</P>
<P>
Although private consumption still remained sluggish at the moment,
a revival was expected to come during the course of the year, the
institute predicted. Meanwhile, it also saw signs of an improvement in
construction sector.
</P>
<P>
The latest monthly economic report of the DIW also noted that the
positive development on the domestic market came at time when the
country's dynamic export expansion had appeared to slow down slightly
for the moment.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, exports would continue to be the main driving force
behind Germany's economic growth in 1998, the DIW said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
