<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-27 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Moves Toward Repealing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Knesset (parliament)
Wednesday passed the preliminary reading on a bill that would
repeal the direct election for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The bill was approved by a vote of 50-45. But this was only the
first step to abolish the direct election law.
</P>
<P>
Under Israeli law, it requires only a relative majority to pass
the preliminary stage, but will need the support of 61 members of
the 120-seat Knesset to pass three more readings.
</P>
<P>
The bill was submitted by ruling Likud Party member Uzi Landau
and opposition Labor Party member Yossi Beilin.
</P>
<P>
They said that the direct election system gives the prime
minister too much power and is not good for a democratic country.
</P>
<P>
Both Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Labor
leader Ehud Barak are opposed to repealing the direct election.
</P>
<P>
The direct election law was only put into effect in 1996.
Before then, Israelis had voted for parties under a system that
limited the power of the prime minister and made it easier to
topple the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
