<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Discusses Changes Affecting State Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwaiti Higher Council of
Planning, an advisory and supervising organ for economic planning,
held a meeting Wednesday to discuss two reports on the state
budget, the official news agency Kuna reported.
</P>
<P>
The two reports were submitted by the Economic and Financial
Committee.
</P>
<P>
One report deals with the committee's opinion about the general
guidelines of the state budget for the fiscal year 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
The other covers the committee's assessment of the financial
and economic situation in the country with regard to the drop of
world oil prices and the impact on the budget for the fiscal year
of 1997-1998 ending on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is expected to have a deficit of 3.3 billion U.S.
dollars in the fiscal year 1997-1998 due to the slump of oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
The committee has suggested a series of urgent measures topped
by reduction of spendings, increase of non-oil revenues and
reconsideration of the subsidization policy without affecting the
limited-income earners.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Crown Prince and Prime Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah
Al-Salem Al-Sabah, who chaired the meeting, underlined the need to
adopt reforms in a bid to face the current changes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
