<HEADLINE> Arafat-Gingrich Talks "Beginning of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RAMALLAH, WEST BANK, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians and
the U.S. Congress have created "a real dialogue" by the talks
between Palestinian National Authority (PNA) leader Yasser Arafat
and U.S. House Speaker Newt Gingrich, Palestinian officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing outside Arafat's office, where the
90-minute talks between Arafat and Gingrich were held, Palestinian
Planning and International Minister Nabil Sha'ath said the talks
were "frank and positive."
</P>
<P>
"We have established a mechanism to visit each other, to
contact each other... We have created a real dialogue with the
U.S. Congress for the first time. I think this is important,"
Sha'ath said.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich also described the talks as "very good, very
positive." "We focused on ways to push forward the peace
process," he said, "We believe it is possible (for us) to work
together."
</P>
<P>
The talks were held amid doubts over whether the PNA would
cancel the scheduled meeting to protest against Gingrich's siding
with Israeli government, especially his remarks that Jerusalem
should remain united and eternal capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich insisted at the news briefing that his stand on the
status of Jerusalem reflected the position of the U.S.
government. "We do have a law which says there should be an
embassy in Jerusalem," he said, referring to a bill passed by the
Congress in 1995 which mandating that the U.S. Embassy in Tel Aviv
should be moved to Jerusalem by May 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, there is a lot of disagreements about that," he
admitted.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Sha'ath said Arafat explained very clearly the
Palestinian stand on the issue of Jerusalem and Gingrich
"listened very carefully and in a positive way."
</P>
<P>
"We were not in an argument mood," he added.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Gingrich would leave for Amman in the
afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
