<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-27 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Saudi Arabia Agree to Cooperate Over Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Saudi Foreign Minister Saud
al-Faisal said on Wednesday that his country and Iran have agreed
to cooperate in preventing world oil prices from further falling,
the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have agreed to draw up a long-term strategy
to stop the oil prices from slumping with the assistance from
other oil producers, al-Faisal said in a meeting with Chairman of
Iran's State Expediency Council Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi official said that cooperation between Saudi Arabia
and Iran would be effective in stopping the drop of the oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The world oil prices are falling sharply in recent months
mainly due to a low demand from Asian countries in financial
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani, former Iranian president, said that to shore up the
oil prices is an area of cooperation between Tehran and Riyadh,
adding the two countries along with other oil producers are
expected to make a serious decision in this respect.
</P>
<P>
He said the Islamic nations need unity and solidarity more than
before to settle regional crisis and maintain peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
He called for multilateral cooperation among Iran, Saudi
Arabia, Syria and other states to attain the goal.
</P>
<P>
Al-Faisal arrived here on Tuesday for a two-day visit. He left
here Wednesday afternoon after holding the second round of talks
with his Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharrazi, Tehran Radio said.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two officials underlined the need of
understanding and cooperation between Tehran and Riyadh on
regional issues.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that regional issues, such as those of Iraq and
Afghanistan, can not be resolved through military ways, but only
through political talks and peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Faisal said the two countries share the view on need for
cooperation between the Organization of the Islamic Conference and
the United Nations to help end the Afghan crisis.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also exchanged views about the
recent Indian nuclear tests. Kharrazi said that nuclear tests
would pose threat to regional security, calling on regional
countries to join efforts to announce a region free from nuclear
weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
