<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-27 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gingrich Meets King Hussein, Other Jordanian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 27 (Xinhua) -- United States Congress Speaker Newt
Gingrich here Wednesday met King Hussein of Jordan and discussed
with him on the long-stalled Middle East peace process and the
U.S.- Jordanian relations.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich briefed the king on his current tour in the
region. The details of their meeting have not been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, he dined with Hussein and his U.S.-born
wife, Queen Nour, at the king's Peace Gate Palace outside Amman.
</P>
<P>
Before the meeting, Gingrich held separate talks with the
king's heir Hassan, President of the Jordanian Upper House of
Parliament Zeid Rifai as well as Speaker of the Lower House of
Parliament Saad Hail El-Sorour, official Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival in Amman Wednesday afternoon from visit to the
Palestinian self-ruled West Bank, Gingrich told reporters that he
had found there was willingness from both the Israeli and the
Palestinian sides to continue the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The peace process has been deadlocked for 15 months due to the
Jewish settlement expansion in Arab East Jerusalem.and the delayed
Israeli troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was deeply committed to the restoration of the peace
talks between Israel and the Palestinians, he added.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich wrapped up his four-day visit to Israel and the
Palestinian self-rule areas earlier Wednesday after giving
unreserved backing to Israel's claim of sovereignty over the
occupied Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The East Jerusalem was seized from Arabs in the 1967 Mideast
War by Israelis before the Jewish state formally annexed it and
declared that it was the state's capital in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, which once ruled the East Jerusalem, calls for its
return to the Palestinians and King Hussein considers himself as
the guardian of the Muslim shrines in Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
