<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran on Wednesday announced an ambitious plan of
exporting the Caspian Sea oil through Iranian territory.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Oil Minister Ali Majedi said that Iran has planned to
transfer oil of the Caspian Sea littoral states in three stages.
</P>
<P>
The first stage is to lay a 392-kilometer pipeline from the
Caspian port of Neka in Mazadaran province to Tehran. The Caspian
oil from Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan and Turkmenistan will be
transferred to two Iranian refineries in Tehran and Tabriz to swap
with Iranian oil in the Persian Gulf terminals.
</P>
<P>
The first-phase project, with a budget of 400 million
U.S. dollars, would be open to international bidding next week in
London. The cost would be paid from the sale of the crude oil in
the swap deal.
</P>
<P>
The second stage is to transfer the Caspian oil to two other
Iranian refineries in Isfahan and Arak, central Iran; and the
third one is to pipe the Caspian oil to the Kharg terminal in the
Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran and Saudi Arabia signed an agreement on
Wednesday aimed at promoting bilateral cooperation in the fields
of economy, trade, technology, science, sports, culture and joint
investment.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also calls for cooperation in industries, mining,
transportation, trade exchange, tourism and providing businessmen
of the two sides with necessary facilities.
</P>
<P>
The agreement underlined the importance of cooperation in the
fields of air and sea transportation and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Saudi Prince al-Waleed bin Talal has signed a deal
worth 250 million U.S. dollars with Lebanon to build a luxury
hotel complex in Beirut, the Daily Star newspaper reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The complex includes a 260-room seaside hotel and luxury
housing units and commercial shops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
