<HEADLINE> Rwanda's Ex-Govt Soldiers Trial Going on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Counsel of War Tuesday
continued trial proceedings of two former government soldiers and
a university lecturer who were involved in the 1994 genocide,
state-run radio reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Second-lieutenant Pierre Bizimana, private Aloys Mazimpaka,
and Dr. Martin Kageruka were charged with acts of genocide and
crimes against humanity, which included the massacre of Queen
Rosalia Gicanda and six of her relatives, in Butare prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Mazimpaka confessed his involvement and apologized for his
acts and asked for leniency, a Rwanda News Agency report quoted
the radio as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kageruka was charged with distributing arms to Hutu militia
who have led the attack on Huye commune in which many Tutsis were
killed.
</P>
<P>
The trial of these former government soldiers had opened in
southern Butare town early this month. The prosecutor requested
death penalty for Bizimana and Kaberuka, and life sentence for
private Mazimpaka. 
</P>
