<HEADLINE> Lesotho's New PM to Be Elected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Lesotho Congress for
Democracy (LCD), which won overwhelmingly in last week's general
election, will elect the country's new prime minister Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The LCD's caucus will meet in capital Maseru to name the
candidate who will succeed outgoing 79-year-old prime minister
Ntsu Mokhehle, South African Press Association reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
LCD leader and Deputy Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili and
party deputy leader and Foreign Minister Kelebone Maope are the
two main contenders for the position.
</P>
<P>
The party will advise King Letsie III of their decision, and
the new prime minister will be sworn in Friday and form a new
government later.
</P>
<P>
The LCD raked in 78 of the 80 national assembly seats in the
election, the third in the tiny mountain kingdom since its
independence in 1966.
</P>
<P>
Ailing Mokhehle, who is receiving medical treatment in
Johannesburg, South Africa, is expected to tender his resignation
Thursday to pave the way for the inauguration of his successor.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the results of the Qene constituency, south of
Maseru, were Wednesday afternoon still outstanding because of a
re-counting at the request of the Sefate Democratic Union.
</P>
<P>
Earlier results showed that an LCD candidate won the
constituency during Monday and Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
