<HEADLINE> Orchards and Vineyards Decline in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Romania, one of the 10 richest
countries in the world in orchards and vineyards, is witnessing
sharp decline in the plantations.
</P>
<P>
According to Gheorghe Glaman, President of Romanian
Horticulture Owners Association and President of Romanian
Horticulture Society, over 70 percent of the vineyards and the
orchards were transferred into private property as a result of the
application of Land Law. Most of the new owners could not take
proper care of the plantations due to lack of equipment, financial
means and expertise. Major vineyards and orchards were thus
cleared and transformed into arable land.
</P>
<P>
Orchard areas declined from 242,000 hectares to 214,000
hectares and the fruit harvest decreased from 1,570 thousand tones
in 1989 to only 1,300 thousand tones.
</P>
<P>
The plight of the viticulture is even more terrible. Almost
half of vineyards were planted with hybrids banned in other
countries, which seriously affect the quality of the Romanian
wines and exports.
</P>
<P>
Specialists voiced deep concern over this situation. They
proposed setting up a fund for supporting the development of the
orchards and vineyards.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
