<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Production in CIS Improving: FAO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. food agency said
Wednesday that the food situation in most of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) is gradually improving and food aid needs
have fallen sharply.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. Department of Public Information quoted the
U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) as saying that the
CIS continues to have vulnerable groups including pensioners,
disabled people and refugees who cannot afford to buy enough food.
</P>
<P>
The CIS is made up of most of the countries that were once part
of the former USSR.
</P>
<P>
Seven Countries (Almenia, Azerbaijan, Georgia, Kyrgyzstan,
Tajikistan, Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan) with a population of 53
million people are classified as low-income food-deficit
countries.
</P>
<P>
Though overall food supplies in the CIS are adequate to meet
demand, FAO said, there are large differences within countries. In
Tajikistan, 16 percent of the population still need assistance to
survive.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, countries such as Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, the
Russian Federation and Ukraine have exportable grain surpluses in
1997/98.
</P>
<P>
FAO statistics show that CIS grain production rose sharply to
156 million tons in 1997, but CIS wheat output for 1998 is forecast
to decline by up to five million tons, with falls expected in
Ukraine and the Russian Federation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
