<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Announces Subsidized Barley Sale to Retaliate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. will subsidize 30,000
tons of its barley for sale to retaliate for Europe's shipment of
subsidized grain to this country, Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Use of the Export Enhancement Program (EEP) to help U.S.
growers "is a measured, targeted response to the European Union's
recent sale of heavily subsidized barley into the United States,"
Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
"Our action today demonstrates how seriously we view the E.U.
sale," he added.
</P>
<P>
He made the decision after widespread complaints from American
farmers and some members of Congress about Europe's sale of 30,000
tons of subsidized Finnish barley to a California feed mill.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. subsidized barley sale will go to Algeria, Cyprus and
Norway. The EEP program, which has not been used since 1996, pays
cash bonuses to purchasers of American farm products, which makes
their prices more competitive.  
</P>
</TEXT>
