<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Finance Reform Bill Triggers Lobbying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Groups on both sides of a debate
on overhauling the political fund-raising laws in the United
States are sending pointed messages in various ways to members of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
The National Right to Life Committee, a leading opponent of
restrictions on donations and issue-oriented advertisements, wrote
lawmakers that a vote for restrictions would hurt their ratings in
the group's annual guide.
</P>
<P>
The League of Women Voters, which supports the legislation
designed to change campaign finance laws, sent out an "action
alert" urging its members: "We must generate a high volume of
pro-reform calls."
</P>
<P>
The National Association of Business Political Action
Committees, worried that the current legislation could be amended
to curtail PAC donations, took out a biting, full-page
advertoisement in a Capitol Hill newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The PACs, or political action committees, are groups that
represent a point of view and parcels out campaign money to
lawmakers or candidates sharing that point of view.
</P>
<P>
That ad began with a dictionary-like entry for the word
"turncoat" and gave the following definition: "A member of
Congress who solicits money from political action committees
(PACs) and then turns around and co-sponsors or votes for
amendments to eliminate or curtail PAC contributions."
</P>
<P>
The ad says that group members gave 56 million dollars in
contributions in the last election, and warns that "We will
vigorously oppose any threats that reduce the fundamental right to
freedom of speech."
</P>
<P>
At issue is a bill that would ban so-called "soft money" -- the
unlimited donations given to political parties by wealthy
individuals, corporations and labor unions -- and restrict
interest groups' ability to air issue ads designed to sway
elections.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives began debating the legislation
last week.
</P>
<P>
The coalition that favors the campaign finance overhaul has
reached beyond its traditional base of good-government groups to
include organizations such as the American Association of Retired
Persons, the National Council of Churches and the Union of
American Hebrew Congregations.
</P>
<P>
"It's quite clear that this is resonating with the American
people," said President Ann McBride of the Common Cause, an
advocacy group for campaign finance overhaul.
</P>
<P>
"Congress may have mistaken frustration for apathy," she said.
"There is not apathy out there on this issue. People are angry and
frustrated."
</P>
<P>
The opponents include some of the biggest political givers on
Capitol Hill, such as the National Rifle Association, which asked
its members to visit their lawmakers at home this week.
</P>
<P>
While most attention has been focused on soft money and issue
ads, PACs reportedly are worried that they might become a target.
</P>
<P>
PACs, the donating arms of special interest groups, can give up
to 10,000 dollars each to a lawmaker in an election cycle -- half
for the primary and the rest for the general election. Some
proposals would curb those donations or eliminate them.
</P>
<P>
"There is an awful lot of hypocrisy among the candidates,"
business PACs spokesman Steve Stockmeyer said. "During the day,
they give speeches against PACs and at night, they're at the
Capitol Hill Club with their hands out, urging PACs to come to
their fund-raisers." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Use on Increase in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Almost one in four of the UK
population now has access to the Internet and a growing number are
using the net to research products to buy, according to a research
published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, carried out by opinion pollster NOP, showed that
the total number of British Internet users reached 10.3 million in
the first three months this year, or 23 percent of the adults,
though many are only using the net for e-mail.
</P>
<P>
Web-surfing is less common, but 13 percent of the population,
or 5.9 million people in the UK, have now used the World Wide Web,
more than double the number a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that the Web is becoming a crucial
research tool for consumers, with two million people using the net
to investigate products and prices before buying.
</P>
<P>
Web users were found to be particularly affluent, with 46
percent having a household income of more than 25,000 pounds
(40,775 U.S. dollars) and 70 percent owning their own home.
</P>
</TEXT>
