<HEADLINE> Kohl Defends His Minister in Nuke Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 27 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
Wednesday gave his firm backing to his embattled environment
minister who faces a call to resign over recent revelations of
contaminated German nuclear waste shipments.
</P>
<P>
At issue is the disclosure last week that some of Germany's
nuclear waste shipments to French and British reprocessing plants
had leaked much more radiation than official standards permitted.
</P>
<P>
At a special parliament debate on Wednesday, the ecologist
Greens party sharply accused Environmental Minister Angela Merkel
of neglecting her duty to supervise the nuclear activities in the
country and called on her to resign to take the responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting the call, Kohl said that Merkel "has been doing
excellent work and is fully capable of carring out her duty with
responsibility".
</P>
<P>
"The German government has done its duty while the nuclear
operators have not," said Kohl in a reference to an earlier
admission by the country's nuclear operators that they had been
informed of the contaminations as early as mid-1980s but had
failed to inform the government.
</P>
<P>
After a stormy debate, the Greens' call for Merkel's
resignation was finally turned down by a majority vote in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the nuclear incident might still has political
repercussions because it came at a time when Kohl is trailing in
polls of voter's support with only four month to go before the
general elections in September this year.
</P>
<P>
The Greens, which hopes to join the main opposition Social
Democratic Party in a new government after the election,
threatened Wednesday to seek the establishment of a parliament
committee to launch further investigations into the scandal.
</P>
</TEXT>
