<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Not Ready for Deployment in Albania: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, May 28 (Xinhua) -- NATO, the 16-nation western
military alliance, admitted Thursday that it was not quite ready
for deployment in Albania, but its planners could work out
detailed action plans within weeks.
</P>
<P>
A NATO official said that the NATO Military Committee, the
highest military authority within the alliance, was given the
mandate a month ago to make detailed studies for options of
sending NATO-led border-monitoring troops to Albania.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the Military Committee had been
considering three options with from small to large troop sizes to
help guard Albania's northern border with the Yugoslavian province
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He quoted United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
as saying that the alliance could not afford too few nor too many
troops.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the manpower had to correspond to the mandate
otherwise NATO troops would fall short of their mission.
</P>
<P>
When asked to elaborate on the number of the largest size of
what NATO described as a preventive force, the NATO official said
that it had to be as large as between 20,000 and 23,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
A considerable force had to be deployed to help guard the
140-kilometer border shared by Albania and Kosovo and the lack of
infrastructure in the Balkan country made the deployment of the
NATO preventive force difficult, he explained.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers agreed during their half-yearly council
meeting on Thursday that all NATO actions must be in conformity
with the United Nations Charter and international law.
</P>
<P>
The NATO official disclosed that it was the first time that
NATO consulted Russia on military action before NATO member states
made a decision.
</P>
<P>
NATO authorities discussed with Russia's permanent
representative to the alliance on Wednesday plans for assistance
to be offered to Albania and NATO foreign ministers were to meet
and discuss with their counterpart Yevgeny Primakov the issue of
Kosovo during the NATO-Russia Permanent Joint Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
When pressed for a definite reply whether Russia supported or
opposed NATO intervention in the Balkans, the NATO official
only said that Russia did not say it would not participate in the
preventive force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
