<HEADLINE> NATO Decides to Assist Albania, Macedonia in Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) decided on Thursday to launch
NATO-led assistance programs in Albania and Macedonia to help
secure their borders with Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The programs include a military exercise involving ground and
air forces in Albania in August and another in Macedonia in
September and the establishment of a NATO/Partnership for Peace
(PFP) liaison in Albania's capital.
</P>
<P>
Both Albania and Macedonia are PFP member states.
</P>
<P>
NATO's standing force in the Mediterranean was authorized by
the foreign ministers council meeting to make a port call to
Durres in Albania in early July and the measures are seen as a
sign of the NATO's display of PFP solidarity.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers also expressed their support for the
United Nations and the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe in monitoring activity as well as for NATO's preventive
deployments in Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
A NATO statement released after the meeting said that the
western military alliance was "deeply concerned by the situation
in Kosovo" and it deplored "the continuing use of violence in
suppressing political dissent or in pursuit of political change."
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed that the problems of Kosovo could best
be resolved through a process of open and unconditional dialogue
between authorities in Belgrade and the leadership of the ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We support a political solution which provides an enhanced
status for Kosovo, preserves the territorial integrity of the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and safeguards the human and civil
rights of all inhabitants of Kosovo," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
