<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Companies Keep High Confidence in HK: Japanese Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Latest statistics show that
Japanese companies, far from being pessimistic about their current
status in Hong Kong, are in fact very upbeat about the future
here, Kunihiko Makita, consul-general of Japan in Hong Kong said
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing at the dinner reception hosted by the Chinese
Manufacturers' Association of Hong Kong, Makita said that the
results of a survey conducted by the Consulate of Japan among 737
Japanese companies in Hong Kong last month showed that the
companies questioned have actually increased the number of staff
for the period from July 1997 to March 1998.
</P>
<P>
During the same period more companies in the survey said they
have expanded their office or factory space than those who have
reduced their working area, Makita said.
</P>
<P>
When these companies were asked what their strategies were for
the next three years, more than 60 percent of the Japanese
companies questioned planned at least to maintain their current
size, while 25 percent were actually planning to expand their
operations over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, nearly one third of the Japanese companies questioned
from the commerce and manufacturing sectors confirmed they would
be expanding their operations over the next three years, the
consul general said.
</P>
<P>
Makita said despite the economic slowdown in Hong Kong due to
the current Asian economic crisis, there are still grounds for
optimism for the future since all the sound economic fundamentals
of Hong Kong still exist.
</P>
<P>
The proven success of the "one country, two systems" principle
and the determined support from China's central government
obviously are sources of confidence, Makita said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
