<HEADLINE> Palestinian Lawmakers Set No-Confidence Vote in PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Legislative
Council (PLC) has set Saturday for a vote of no-confidence in the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) headed by Yasser Arafat for
its inaction.
</P>
<P>
This decision was made by the legislative body in West Bank
city Ramallah on Thursday after 28 legislators, including several
PLC members of Arafat's own Fatah faction, signed a petition in
favor of holding such a vote.
</P>
<P>
They were to protest the PNA's failure to approve the 1998
budget or implement the laws passed by the PLC, according to the
Jerusalem-based Palestinian press service JMCC.
</P>
<P>
During Thursday's session, the seventh session of the second
term, the PLC was briefed on the report on allocating the PNA
budget for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Several PLC members in the past several days have threatened to
table a no-confidence motion to the PLC, saying the PNA has not
implemented the long-promised reforms following charges of
high-level corruption and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
Arafat signed on Thursday a number of laws such as the Civil
Service Law and the Law for Monitoring Precious Minerals. But this
could not prevent some lawmakers from submitting their
no-confidence motion for voting.
</P>
<P>
PLC Speaker Abu Ala also tried to prevent the lawmakers from
setting a date for the no-confidence vote. But Azmi Suhabi, an
independent legislator from Ramallah, collected signatures in
favor of holding a special session on Saturday from 28 members,
enough to put it on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here said that Arafat and his PNA would
survive any no-confidence vote because the majority of the
88-member PLC supports Arafat and even if the motion did pass, it
could only lead to a cabinet reshuffle by Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian legislative body was formed in January 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
