<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Scholars on Economic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Stabilizing Thai baht, keeping
ample foreign reserves and maintaining public trust in the
government's economic policies are what should be done to get
Thailand out of the economic mire, a famous Thai scholar said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Somchai Pacapakviwat, a prestigious scholar specializing in
both politics and economics, made the remarks at a seminar on
economic crisis, organized by the Chinese Studies Center of
Chulalongkorn University and attended by both Chinese and Thai
experts.
</P>
<P>
Somchai briefed the experts on the government's steps in
solving the current economic problems.
</P>
<P>
First, stabilizing the exchange rate of Thai baht against hard
currencies; second, restructuring the financial sector by closing
56 finance companies last year and taking over another 7 companies
last week; third, controlling the spread of bad debts so as to
restore confidence in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Another famous Thai scholar, associate professor Sompop
Manarungsang from the Chulalongkorn University, analyzed the root
causes of the economic and financial crisis in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
He said bubble economy should be blamed for the crisis. Big
bubbles in non-manufacturing sectors such as real estate and stock
market were blown up by the massive influx of short-term,
low-interest loans from abroad after the country opened its
financial sector in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Political instability in the country, featured by the frequent
changes of finance ministers and central bank governors, further
worsened the economic situation, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kovit Posayanon, another professor from the Chulalongkorn
University, reviewed the measures the government has taken to
reform the financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that financial institutions should attach
importance to long-term objectives research and plans of sustained
development.
</P>
</TEXT>
