<HEADLINE> Kournikova Enters Third Round at French Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Russian teenager Anna Kournikova
reached the third round of the women's singles after a
straight-sets win over Katarina Studenikov of Slovakia after rain
delayed the start of play by over four hours at the French Open
tennis tournament on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Russian spent 72 minutes dismissing her
opponent for a 6-2, 7-6 (7-2) victory.
</P>
<P>
The 13th-seeded Kournikova now faces Asa Carlsson of Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Fourth seed Arantxa Sanchez Vicario of Spain also advanced with
a confident 6-2, 6-3 win over Catalina Cristea of Romania.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old Sanchez, a winner here in 1989 and 1994, next
faces either Alexandra Fusai of France or Tara Snyder of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Miho Saeki kept Japanese hopes alive when she beat Laurence
Andretto of France 6-1, 7-6 (7-5) to reach the third round.
</P>
<P>
She now plays Chanda Rubin of the United States, who beat
Tatiana Panova of Russia 6-1, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
In the men's actions, former world number one Thomas Muster of
Austria powered his way into the third-round by beating Germany's
Nicolas Kiefer 6-2, 6-1, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Muster now plays either Christophe Van Garsse of Belgium or
Scott Draper of Australia for a place in the last-sixteen.
</P>
