<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Producer Inflation Rises in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 28 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's producer
inflation ticked up to 2.9 percent year-on-year last month from
2.3 percent in March, according to the latest statistics released
by the Central Statistical Services (CSS).
</P>
<P>
It was expected in the market that the producer inflation
would only rise by 2.4 percent in April, local media reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The CSS figures showed a monthly rise in the producer price
index of one percent following price increases across the
spectrum of agricultural, mining, beverage and paper products,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The index of imported goods was unchanged form March but up
1.3 percent from April last year, influenced by the recent
weakness of the Rand.
</P>
<P>
Economists noted that the year-on-year increase was the first
since March last year. They predicted producer inflation would
end the year at just more than four percent, and the average for
the year would be about 3.5 percent, well below last year's 7.1
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCTAD Official Says Small Firms Have Big Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Small and medium-sized enterprises
(SMEs) can be leading entrepreneurial engines for development but
many governments in developing countries have not realized the
importance, said a senior United Nations official here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Actions are needed to develop the enormous potential that
these firms have and to stimulate growth and development through
foreign direct investment (FDI)," said U.N. Conference on Trade
and Development (UNCTAD) Secretary-General Rubens Ricupero.
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD chief made the remarks at launching his agency's new
report, entitled A Handbook on Foreign Direct Investment by Small
and Medium-sized Enterprises: Lessons from Asia.
</P>
<P>
"We want to encourage governments to build healthy SME sectors
and cooperate in stimulating the international investment
potential of these firms," Ricupero said. "Actions can be taken
through greater exchanges of information on SME experiences,
harmonizing regulations and simplifying regulatory provisions."
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD report is based on case studies of the economic
structures and policies of selected Asian economies including
Japan, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, South Korea, and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Current levels of FDI in Asia by SMEs, accounting for barely 10
percent of total regional FDI, are below their full potential,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD suggests that the mix of policies and programs be
designed to establish monitoring and performance systems;
encourage the development of growth-oriented and internationally
oriented SMEs in the domestic economy; provide accurate
information to foreign investors that are SMEs.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for encouraging linkages between SMEs across
borders; providing appropriate incentives to SMEs and their access
to support services and infrastructure; and addressing specific
impediments and barriers to foreign direct invest by SMEs.
</P>
<P>
The report has found that obstacles the SMEs are facing in
investing abroad include unfair competition, complex business
regulations, difficult investment approval systems and corruption.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-three percent of small investors and 71 percent of
medium-sized investors questioned said corruption by low-level
officials was a major problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
