<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Researchers Warn Of More Deaths From Teen Smoking In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Anti-smoking groups warn that China
will have an increase in the number of smoking-related deaths in
the next three decades unless steps are taken to curb teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
The annual number of smoking-related deaths will climb to 2
million by the year 2025, compared with 750,000 now, and most of
them will come from today's adolescents, a group of health
officials, doctors, educators, and representatives of the World
Health Organization were told at a meeting on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held to discuss ways of keeping young people
away from cigarettes, and ways of stopping tobacco advertising and
the images of smoking on TV.
</P>
<P>
China reported an increase in smoking among males aged 15 to
25, an increase of as much as 6 percentage points since the
1984-1996 period.
</P>
<P>
The average age for the first puff in 1996 was about 19, or 3
years earlier than it was in 1984, according to a recent national
survey of smoking patterns in China. Almost 90 percent of the
smokers started before the age of 19.
</P>
<P>
To make matters worse, many children are becoming victims of
passive smoking, because 90 percent of the smokers puff away in
public places and 70 percent of them do so at home, says
Prof. Zhang Yifang, vice president of the China Association of
Tobacco or Health.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the meeting complained about the images of
movie stars with cigarettes dangling from their lips and sports
matches boldly sponsored by tobacco giants that encourage young
people to just light up. "Many teenagers can't resist the
temptation of a small cigarette when smoking looks enjoyable or
fashionable," says Zhang Lichuan, an official with the Beijing
Municipal Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yifang told Xinhua that his association intends to push
for a ban of cigarette sales to people under 18, but efforts have
so far proven less than fruitful. "The work is really tough since
the tobacco industry is still a leading taxpayer, and it creates
new consumers constantly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has started prohibiting some tobacco stores from
selling cigarettes to minors, the first move of its kind in the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
