<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Germany's third largest commercial
bank, Commerzbank, confirmed Thursday that it has bought a 29.79
percent stake in South Korea's Korea Exchange Bank (KEB).
</P>
<P>
A letter of intent was signed on the deal valued at about 440
million marks (about 250 million U.S. dollars), the
Frankfurt-based Commerzbank said.
</P>
<P>
The final contract was due to be signed by the end of July, the
bank added.
</P>
<P>
The move, aimed at increasing the German bank's exposure in
Asia, would make Commerzbank the second largest shareholder in the
KEB, second only to Bank of Korea.
</P>
<P>
So far, Commerzbank only has a representative office in South
Korea and a minority holding in KEB's subsidiary Korea Merchant
Bank. 
