<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Conference Calls for End of Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from governments,
employers and trade unions will strive to abolish extreme forms of
child labor when they meet here next week.
</P>
<P>
At the opening of the 86th session of the International Labor
Conference on June 2, they will receive hundreds of young people
arriving here from a "Global March Against Child Labor."
</P>
<P>
The International Labor Organization (ILO), the organizer of
the conference, is preparing a convention and a recommendation to
abolish extreme forms of child labor immediately.
</P>
<P>
As stated by ILO Director-General Michel Hansenne, the annual
meeting to last through June 18 will try to "identify, confront
and eliminate without delay" the extreme forms of child labor.
</P>
<P>
Currently, millions of children are exposed daily to
exploitation, risks of accident, diseases and deaths.
</P>
<P>
The ILO estimates that 250 million children at age 5-14 in the
developing countries have to work full time or part time, of whom
61 percent are in Asia, 32 percent in Africa, and 7 percent in
Latin America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
