<HEADLINE> China Increasing Spending On Roads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government plans to
spend 40 billion yuan more on highway construction in 1998,
bringing total spending for the year to 160 billion yuan,
according to government sources.
</P>
<P>
Of that amount, 90 billion yuan will be used for key road
projects, 50 billion yuan for improving highway networks and hubs,
and 20 billion yuan for roads in rural and poor areas.
</P>
<P>
The government has goals for highway construction in the Ninth
Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000), and wants to reach those two years
ahead of schedule, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Five-Year Plan calls for 24,000 km of new roads to bring
the total mileage in China to 1.25 million km.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, China is expected to build 1,117 km of expressways,
296 km more than the plans call for. 
</P>
