<HEADLINE> Chinese Trade Official Optimistic About Trade With Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The trade of China's inland areas
with Hong Kong could still see improvement this year, because most
exports to Hong Kong could be re-exported to Europe and the United
States, where the economy is growing steadily.
</P>
<P>
Wang Wende, the director of the Taiwan, Hong Kong and Macao
Affairs Department under the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, says that trade between the inland and Hong Kong
increased at a slower rate in the first quarter than for the same
1997 period, but was still higher than the average growth of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from Customs show that inland exports to Hong Kong,
its second biggest trade partner, were worth 9.94 billion
U.S. dollars, while imports from the region were worth 1.47
billion U.S. dollars, up 15.1 and 5.2 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Inland exports to Hong Kong of garments, electric machinery and
plastic products rose by 29.1, 12.2 and 17.6 percent respectively
while the shoe exports doubled.
</P>
<P>
The inland increased imports from Hong Kong, adding about 28
percentage points from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong re-exported most of its imports from the inland
China, 55 percent of them to North America and European Union.
</P>
<P>
Trade experts here believe that inland exports to Hong Kong
will continue to grow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
