<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Calls for Actions Against Tobacco Use Among Youths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
has urged the international community to take tough action to
prevent children and young people from smoking.
</P>
<P>
"Unless tough action is taken immediately, the tobacco epidemic
will prematurely claim the lives of about 250 million children and
young people alive today," said WHO Deputy Director-General ad
interim Dr Fernando Antezana Thursday in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came on the occasion of World No-Tobacco Day 1998
on May 31 which is dedicated this year to children under the theme
"Growing Up Without Tobacco."
</P>
<P>
Antezana said that in many countries, tobacco use was rising
among young people, while the age of smoking initiation is
declining. The majority of smokers began in their teenage years or
earlier.
</P>
<P>
However, he believed if young people did not begin smoking
before the age of 20, they were unlikely to start as adults.
</P>
<P>
The WHO estimates that about one-third of the adult population
smokes and that out of two smokers, who started at a young age and
continue smoking throughout their lives, one will ultimately be
killed by a tobacco-related illness.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say there are a number of complex and interacting
reasons why children and adolescents begin smoking. Often, they
mistake smoking for an attribute of independence.
</P>
<P>
They say that the image of independence has been skillfully built
by tobacco advertizing and promotional activities.
</P>
<P>
"Early use of tobacco products is purposeful and is the result of
demand created by the tobacco industry," said Director of the United
States Office on Smoking and Health Michael Eriksen.
</P>
<P>
"As adults, we must stand up for the health of the world's
children, even in the face of considerable opposition," Antezana
said. "It is time for all of us to make those critical decisions,
which will truly allow our children to grow up without tobacco."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
