<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Developing Use of Ethnic Minority Medicines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The traditional medicines used by
China's ethnic minority groups have gained in popularity over the
past 20 years and there are now 128 hospitals and 10,000 people
involved in using them.
</P>
<P>
There are 52 hospitals that specialize in traditional Tibetan
medicine, Zhu Guoben, chairman of the Chinese Society of
Traditional Ethnic Medicine, told a national symposium on
traditional medicines that started in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The traditional medicines of 30 ethnic groups have been
collected in a systematic way, and the medicines of the Tibetan,
Mongolian, Uygur, Dai, and Zhuang nationalities have done
especially well, Zhu says.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1970s, local governments have set up standards for
Tibetan and Mongolian medicines that have been added to the
national pharmacopoeia, he said.
</P>
<P>
There are at least 30 factories in Qinghai Province, the Tibet
and Xinjiang Uygur autonomous regions, and other areas producing
400 types of traditional medicine, some of them producing
brand-name products and making a name for themselves.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the symposium is to get more ethnic minority
medicines into the domestic and world market, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
The three-day symposium is sponsored by the Chinese Society for
the Traditional Medicine of Ethnic Groups.
</P>
<P>
The society will publish a guide book on Chinese traditional
medicines of ethnic minorities based on information gathered at
the symposium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
