<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 28 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and France
Thursday signed a defense cooperation agreement over the exchange
of military personnel and information.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed in Cape Town, aims to promote personnel
training through exchange programs, encourage research and
development cooperation between the two countries' defense
industries, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
It also paves the way for the exchange of information on
development and modernization projects, for exchanging
researchers and engineers, and for joint defense research
programs and export possibilities.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, South African Defense
Minister Joe Modise described the agreement as another milestone
in growing ties between South Africa and France.
</P>
<P>
French Ambassador to South Africa Tristan D'albis, who signed
the agreement on behalf of his government, said that it reflected
the reality of the improved military relations between the two
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
