<HEADLINE> 5 Leftist Rebels Killed in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Five suspected members of the
leftist rebel group, the New People's Army (NPA), were killed
during separate armed encounters with the Philippine government
troops over the weekend, the military said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Brig. Gen. Melchor Rosales, chief of Civil Military Operations
of the Philippines' Armed Forces, said Thursday that the
government troops encountered the rebels in separate battles,
killing five rebels in the southern provinces of Camarines Sur and
South Cotabato.
</P>
<P>
Rosales said a lot of rifles were also seized after the
gunfights in the clash areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Col. Nestor Castillo, a military spokesman,
dismissed charges of the National Democratic Front (NDF) that the
military has allegedly violated an earlier agreement on the
suspension of military operations.
</P>
<P>
Jalandoni, a negotiator of the NDF which led the NPA,
reportedly charged that the military attacked NPA camps and
captured wounded guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Castillo said the NDF's refusal to declare a joint ceasefire
with the government was an indication of their insincere attitude
in forging peace with the government.
</P>
<P>
The NDF, a leftist alliance created by the Communist Party of
the Philippines in the late 1960s, has fought the government for
decades. The group began its on-and-off exploratory peace talks
with the government six years ago, but the two sides have so far
failed to reach any agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
