<HEADLINE> Moroccan King Winds up Visit to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Moroccan King Hassan II wound up his
three-day visit here Thursday, during which he coordinated stance
with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on salvaging the stalled
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak sent Hassan off at Cairo International Airport at noon
Thursday, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency did not give details about their talks. But Arab
League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid termed Hassan's visit
as "an important step toward a concerted Arab plan of action."
</P>
<P>
Hassan's visit came at a time when the Israeli-Palestinian
talks have been deeply stranded due to Israel's intransigence, and
Arab countries are pushing for an Arab summit to discuss the
peace-making after the U.S. has failed to persuade Israel to
accept its proposal.
</P>
<P>
Israel has turned down a U.S. formula calling on it to pullback
its troops from 13 percent more of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The MENA has quoted an Egyptian diplomat as saying that
Hassan's visit to Egypt was partly in preparation for the summit,
proposed by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Hassan and Mubarak witnessed the signing of several agreements
and protocols on cooperation between the two countries in
judiciary, oil, tourism, agriculture, electricity and fishery.
</P>
<P>
A free trade zone agreement was also signed to boost bilateral
trade which currently stands at 30 million dollars annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
