<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Hold Extraordinary Session of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's People's Consultative
Assembly (MPR) will hold an extraordinary session at the end of
this year or early next year to set the time for the general
elections, according to House Speaker Harmoko.
</P>
<P>
Harmoko told reporters that President B.J. Habibie and leaders
of the House of Representatives (DPR) have met to discuss how to
speed up the holding of general elections here today.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, DPR/MPR Chairman Harmoko said, the
President expressed the government's willingness to accelerate the
holding of elections.
</P>
<P>
Harmoko said the House has already formed a team that will
review and amend the election law so that general elections could
be held soon.
</P>
<P>
The team will have to draft bills to amend the election law,
including acts on the formation of political parties and the
structure of the MPR, DPR and the provincial legislative bodies,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The House has also formed a team to draft legislation aimed at
improving the country's legal system and economy, he added.
</P>
<P>
The House Speaker said Both government officials and
legislators would need to discuss the bills together, if possible
within six months.
</P>
<P>
Habibie, who assumed the presidential office last Thursday, has
pledged to call for fresh elections as soon as possible to pave
the way for the formation of a new MPR which will choose a new
President and Vice President. 
</P>
</TEXT>
