<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Banks Strong Enough to Weather Difficulties: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Even if bad debts do rise and
profits are lower, Hong Kong banks have the fundamental capital
strength to manage their way through the current difficulties,
said a senior Hong Kong monetary official on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
David Carse, deputy chief executive of the Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA), described the Asian financial crisis as a
"one-in-a-lifetime" event, which is bound to have an impact on the
banks' funding, loan growth, asset quality and profitability.
</P>
<P>
"However, the Hong Kong banking sector is robust enough to
withstand this," the official told a press conference reviewing
the performance of the banking sector in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Deposit growth was sluggish between January and March, up 1.8
percent compared with the December quarter while domestic loans
falling 0.8 percent in the period, he noted.
</P>
<P>
And the regional crisis and the slowdown of the domestic
economy led to some deterioration in asset quality, Carse
continued. For the local banks, loans overdue for more than three
months increased from 1.57 percent at end-December 1997 to 1.97
percent at end-March 1998, while overall problem loans, measured
by classified loans, grew from 2.08 percent to 2.77 percent.
</P>
<P>
But they are still low by international standards, the official
noted.
</P>
<P>
"Further deterioration can be expected in the coming months
although not to the extent seen in other parts of Asia. However,
even deterioration occurs, banks have substantial protection from
continued operating profits, existing bad debt provisions and high
capital adequacy ratios," the official pointed out.
</P>
<P>
All local banks made profits in the first quarter, though lower
compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
"Lower profitability is not by itself a cause for concern in
terms of systemic stability because banks remain highly
capitalized and highly liquid," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
