<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Coach Sees Brazil as Favourite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Brazil remains the favourite for the
coming World Cup in France while Asian outfit Saudi Arabia might
raise a few eyebrows, Italian coach Cesare Maldini said here
today.
</P>
<P>
"It's too early to make real forecasts," said Maldini, "but
Brazil has players who are the envy of the whole world and is the
favourite to win the competition," Maldini told the reporters.
</P>
<P>
In Maldini's opinion, no outsiders can really hope to upset the
Form Book and make it to the last eight.
</P>
<P>
In Group A, he said Brazil and Norway are to go through; in
Group C, France and Denmark; in Group D, Spain and Bulgaria, with
Nigeria a possible threat; In Group E, Holland and Belgium; in
Group F, Germany and Yugoslavia; in Group G, England and Romania;
and in Group H, Croatia and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
But Maldini warned that Asian side Saudi Arabia might be more
of a threat to hosts France and 1992 European champions Denmark
than Nigeria to the rest of the Group D, which many pundits
believe.
</P>
<P>
He refused to advance forecasts for Group B, where Italy is
playing with Austria, Cameroon and Chile.
</P>
<P>
Instead, Maldini said only that "We know Austria and Chile
better, while Cameroon has lost an important player (Foe), yet
qualified easily."
</P>
<P>
On the individual front, like most of the world, Maldini sees
Brazilian Ronaldo as the one star the World Cup is likely to
confirm as the World No.1, but he also cites Juventus star,
Alessandro Del Piero.
</P>
<P>
"For him, I hope it will be a graduation exam."
</P>
<P>
He also mentioned the Yugoslav Mijatovic, Michael Owen of
England, Iliev of Romania, "some Spaniards" and Marcelo The
Matador Salas, the Chilean star bought by Lazio and one of the
Italy's opponents in the group games.
</P>
<P>
Maldini also believes, with the introduction of the new rules
meant to rule out the tackles from behind, "The players with
better technique will be favoured, but the powerful defenders
should also maintain their space."
</P>
<P>
"England, Scotland and Germany may suffer most," he added.
</P>
<P>
But still, the Italian predicts "many goals, at least in the
first phase, since there are great players taking part." 
</P>
</TEXT>
