<HEADLINE> China Expands Foreign Cooperation in Building Materials Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- China has so far conducted
cooperation with more than 50 countries in the building materials
sector, with foreign investment expanding rapidly to new building
materials, high technology and intensive processing.
</P>
<P>
A large number of building materials projects
financed with loans from the World Bank and the Asian Development
Bank have gone into operation, according to Lei Qianzhi, deputy
director of the State Administration of Building Materials
Industry.
</P>
<P>
And, a group of gigantic technical transformation projects
involving sanitary ceramic production, financed with a 100 million
US dollars loan from Italy, has been going on smoothly in the
provinces of Shaanxi, Shandong, Guangdong, Jilin and Hunan.
</P>
<P>
The official said that since 1997 China has signed cooperation
agreements with the Netherlands, Germany, Tailand, Greece,
Australia, Japan, France and Denmark, witnessing a growing number
of foreign partners in the building materials sector.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that China's exports of building materials
exceeded 2.1 billion US dollars in 1997, and its cement exports
amounted to a record 12 million tons last year, up 46 percent over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
To date, China has cumulatively injected five billion US dollars
in overseas investment into the country's building materials
industry.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the country has also introduced
advanced precalcining kiln production lines from other countries
in recent years and built a number of large and modern-sized cement
plants, adding an annual cement production capacity of 22
million tons.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a number of large float glass production lines
jointly funded by companies from Britain, the US and Japan, with a
daily melting capacity ranging from 500 tons to 700 tons, have
produced good economic returns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
