<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Arrests Four Taiwanese For Espionage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Four people from Taiwan were
arrested and charged with espionage in March this year, state
security officials said here today.
</P>
<P>
Kou Jianming, 42, Han Yueting 35, Chen Shaoyu, 43, and Zhou
Changming, 36, have admitted being sent to the mainland by the
Taiwan "Defense Ministry's Military Intelligence Bureau" to
collect political, economic, and military information.
</P>
<P>
Kou, 42, a Taiwan resident, who is the head of a Taiwan
publishing house, started the China Cross-straits Non-governmental
Exchange Association (CANEA) in 1991 in Taiwan and shortly
afterwards began to spy for the "Military Intelligence Bureau",
which paid for his office in Taiwan and a monthly salary.
</P>
<P>
Kuo was told to recruit agents under the cover of CANEA and to
send them to spy on the mainland. From June 1993 to March 1998,
Kou sneaked into the mainland several times and collected
political, economic, military and social information.
</P>
<P>
He was arrested in mid-March in Beijing and police found
instructions from Taiwan military intelligence on his person.
</P>
<P>
He had brought the other three suspects into CANEA and sent
them to the mainland to spy as well.
</P>
<P>
The state security department has called seven people in for
questioning who may be involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based Association for Relations Across the Taiwan
Straits contacted the Straits Exchange Foundation in Taiwan about
this today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
