<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO, Russia Discuss Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, May 28 (Xinhua) -- NATO foreign ministers are to
discuss the issue of Kosovo with their Russian counterpart Yevgeny
Primakov on Thursday at their Permanent Joint Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
Also on the turmoil in Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia, the
ministers are to discuss assistance to Albania, as a way to fend
off its potential spillover into the neighboring Balkan nation.
</P>
<P>
Russia's permanent military representative to the NATO
headquarters in Brussels has already been consulted on plans to
help Albania. Options available include sending troops there.
</P>
<P>
In addition, on the agenda of the foreign ministers from the 16
NATO nations and Russia is the nuclear non-proliferation and
transparency and further military-to-military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The top NATO diplomats are here Thursday through Friday for a
meeting of the NATO council of foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
And their half-yearly gathering this time is expected to task
NATO military commanders to work out immediate contingencies and
longer-term measures to cope with the crisis in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
An option for them are joint military exercises in Macedonia,
scheduled for September this year, and in Albania, expected to
take place as early as this summer.
</P>
<P>
Both Macedonia and Albania are member states of NATO's
Partnership for Peace (PFP) program and NATO stated that it has to
act to demonstrate solidarity within the PFP framework.
</P>
<P>
Long-term crisis-management measures may include deployment of
NATO-led multinational troops along Albania's northern borders
with Kosovo and possible declaration of a no-fly zone over the
bordering areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
