<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 150-200 Cambodians Killed by Landmines: CMAC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- About 150-200 people were killed
per month in Cambodia although the war has stopped there,
Cambodian Mine Action Center (CMAC) Director Sam Sotha told
reporters here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After a five-year concerted clearance efforts, the CMAC
estimated that there are 4 million to 6 million mines left in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The director said that the dreadful challenge of removal of
every anti-personnel land mine and UXO (unexploded ordnance) will
take a long time, however, in the short term they set an aim of
zero mine incident casualties, according to the Australian
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
Sotha said CMAC's program of mine awareness training and
minefield surveying had reduced mine casualties to zero in some
areas.
</P>
<P>
In five years of operations, 3,000 deminers have cleared 50
million square meters for the loss of one dead and 34 injured,
Sotha said.
</P>
<P>
But the CMAC database still features 2,700 suspected
minefields. New technology, including better mine detectors and
mine flails and explosives snifter dogs, offers the promise of
speeding up the clearance process.
</P>
<P>
The clearance job still comes down to one person working on
hands and knees probing the earth a few centimeters at a time.
</P>
<P>
Sotha said that Australia heads the list of countries providing
15 million Australian dollars (9.5 million U.S. dollars) aid.
</P>
<P>
"My purpose to visit here is to say thank you to the Australian
Government and people and, secondly to beg for a continuation of
support," Sotha said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
