<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moslem Fundamentalists, Police Clash Kills 12 in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 28 (Xinhua) -- At least 12 people have been killed
and many others wounded in a bloody clash between police and a
group of Moslem fundamentalists Wednesday in Lagos, Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The State Police Commissioner, Abubakar Tsav, confirmed that
four policemen were among the dead, while eight Moslem
fundamentalists were killed.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed report, however, put the toll of death at around
30.
</P>
<P>
According to Tsav, the police got a report at about 4:00 a.m.
Wednesday that the fundamentalists, living in the Abule-Egba area
on the outskirts of Lagos, were to attack residents of the area.
</P>
<P>
A team of policemen sent to prevent them were attacked by the
fundamentalists with bows, arrows and guns, resulting in the
death of four policemen, including an inspector.
</P>
<P>
The police then moved in a massive reinforcement of anti-riot
police in 28 vehicles and two armored tanks, and launched an
offensive on the fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
The shoot-out lasted nine hours in the whole area, which was
cordoned off by the police. Eight of the fundamentalists were
killed, while leader Malam Adamu reportedly escaped with bullet
wounds.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen persons, including four adult male members of the
fundamentalists, nine juveniles and three women were arrested by
the police, the commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
The fundamentalists, identified as the Maitatsine sect,
reportedly came to the said area from the Niger Republic in 1989.
They have been having a tense relations with local residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
