<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Trade Deficit Widens in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 28 (Xinhua) -- India's trade deficit widened by
a whopping 6.6 billion U.S. dollars despite a sharp decline in
imports which grew at a rate of 5.8 percent in the fiscal year
1997-98.
</P>
<P>
Economic Survey 1997-98 tabled in parliament Thursday said the
balance of payments situation in 1996-97 and 1997-98 remained
manageable despite some concerns on the export front.
</P>
<P>
India's export growth decelerated to 2.6 percent in 1997-98
from 4.5 percent in 1996-97 after three successive years of
increase ranging from 18 to 20 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
The total imports in the last fiscal year were 40.779 billion
U.S. dollars while the exports were 33.980 billion dollars,
according to provisional figures listed by the survey.
</P>
<P>
The demand for imports has been subdued over the last two
years, reflecting a moderation in industrial activity, it said.
</P>
<P>
A noticeable decline in the growth of external trade in 1996
and 1997, decline in export prices of some major items of
manufactured goods and appreciation of India's currency rupee in
real effective exchange rate terms were caused by both foreign and
domestic factors, said the survey, prepared by the Ministry of
Finance.
</P>
<P>
However, non-oil import recovered in 1997-98 to grow by about
14.5 percent over the corresponding period of the previous year,
when it recorded a meager 5.2 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
Oil imports fell by 20.6 percent in 1997-98 after an average
growth of about 30 percent in the previous two years primarily due
to softening of international prices of crude oil and petroleum
products.
</P>
<P>
The survey called the government to take urgent steps to boost
export, bolster capital markets and cut interest rates, thus
ensuring availability of productive capital to industry for
arresting industrial slowdown of in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
India's industrial growth in 1997-98 slowed down to 4.2 percent
from 7.1 percent the previous year mainly due to decline in
investment.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey said, India's macroeconomic fundamentals
are "reasonably strong" compared to the East Asian countries which
are reeling under financial stress.
</P>
<P>
The survey urged the government to devise "effective (social)
security nets" to shield the poor and vulnerable sections against
income fluctuations and market failures.
</P>
<P>
It predicted earlier that foodgrain production target of 200
million tons in 1997-98 is unlikely to be achieved owing mainly to
the fall in wheat production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
