<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Economy to Rebound once Regional Situation Settles: HKSAR FS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's economy should be
able to rebound expeditiously from the current doldrums, once the
regional situation has settled, Donald Tsang, Financial Secretary
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region government, said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tsang admitted that in the light of a further deterioration in
regional and local economic conditions in the more recent months,
his earlier forecast of economic growth for the current year is
likely to be unattainable.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the 12th International
Travel Expo Hong Kong Thursday, Tsang said what lower level of
growth it should be it was impossible to assess with any precision
at this stage, as the situation in the region continued to be
volatile.
</P>
<P>
"The efficiency of Hong Kong's economy tends to reflect these
external events with their wide implications exceptionally
promptly in various performance indicators. This compounds the
difficulty of forecasting."
</P>
<P>
He added that the SAR Government Economist would be providing a
fuller analysis of the latest situation when he published the
Government's First Quarter Economic Report on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tsang noted that the austere economic situation and the
uncertainties surrounding the region since the outbreak of the
Asian financial turmoil loomed large.
</P>
<P>
"The current sluggishness and financial sector troubles in
Japan add to the stringency while the controversy over nuclear
tests in the sub-continent creates new regional tensions," he
remarked.
</P>
<P>
"Many of the economies in the region, and elsewhere, are
suffering badly. Their growth forecast for this year have been
shaved down substantially, in certain cases to well in the
negative range. Interest rates were in double digits.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong, being what we are, cannot be immune from this
plight," Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
He was confident, however, that with the strong fundamentals,
coupled with the flexibility of adaptation to external shock, and
with the extent of price and cost adjustment, Hong Kong's economy
should be able to rebound expeditiously from the current doldrums,
once the regional situation has settled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
