<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Remains Trapped in Tight Range </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Attempts to talk up the Australian
dollar by Federal Treasurer Peter Costello in New York overnight
had little effect in the foreign exchange market Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The local dollar remained trapped in a tight range for most of
the trading session, closing only slightly higher because of
strength in the Japanese yen and the gold price.
</P>
<P>
The local currency ended the day back above the 62.00 U.S.
cents up from 61.98 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It has just been range trading most of the day, it tested
62.30 U.S. cents a couple of times and there seems to be a very
big sell order there that has capped it during the day," Colonial
State Bank foreign exchange dealer Nick Volanakis said.
</P>
<P>
"The buyers are all lined up around 62.05 U.S. cents."
</P>
<P>
The unit last night dipped to another new near 12-year low of
61.65 U.S. cents in early London trade.
</P>
<P>
In New York, Costello soon after that attempted to distance
Australia from the economic problems in Asia, ruling out further
cuts to economic growth forecasts.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters Costello said the Australian dollar was
trading "on a very stable basis", the low Australian dollar also
made Australia an attractive destination for foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Despite his positive comments, traders have predicted more
downside for the currency.
</P>
<P>
"The market does not seem to have a lot of conviction at this
stage," Volanakis said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was buying 85.42 Japanese yen from 85.29
and 1.1090 German marks from 1.0948. 
</P>
</TEXT>
