<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expects Good Summer Grain Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Though enduring a drought and
floods, China is expecting a good summer grain harvest this year,
according to the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"If there is no major natural disaster in the coming days, the
output will be just a little less than last year's," a ministry
official said today.
</P>
<P>
China harvested nearly 124 billion kilograms of grain last
summer, an all-time high. China has reaped good summer grain
harvests in three consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
This year's summer grain planting area is similar to last year,
said the official.
</P>
<P>
Though the drought in major grain-producing provinces since
last winter had affected the growing of wheat, a major summer
grain crop, rainfall since April has eased the drought, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The drought will affect the grain harvest a little," said the
official.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the problem now facing the grain harvest is
the rainfall in the southern part of the country. The continuous
drizzly climate could make wheat mold without sufficient sun.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has warned local governments to make preparations
for the harvesting and storing of wheat.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Water Resources also warned that China may face
more severe flooding this year than in previous years. Southern
provinces such as Jiangxi, Hunan, Fujian and Guangdong have
suffered flooding in 100,000 hectares of crops.
</P>
<P>
To minimize the losses, the ministry has sent working teams to
flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
One-fourth of China's annual grain output comes from summer
harvest. The latest prediction from the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences said that the country is expected to harvest 497-to-500
billion kilograms of grain this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
