<HEADLINE> Chirac to Visit Lebanon for the Third Time in Two Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 28 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac will
pay a two-day visit to Lebanon from Saturday, the third since he
took office two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) said that the visit by Chirac comes at
a time when the Middle East peace process is blocked, and a feeling
of distrust toward the United States is on the rise among Arab
countries following its failure to persuade Israel to accept a
partial withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the European Union is also trying to play a full
part as a political partner in the efforts to revive the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
AFP said that the reason for Chirac to repeatedly visit "the
nation of cedar" is that he has long chosen it as its "natural
gate" for restoring France's influence among Arab countries, as
Lebanon has strong cultural and historical links with France.
</P>
<P>
Chirac will meet with his Lebanese counterpart Elias Hrawi,
Prime Minister Rafic Hariri and parliament speaker Nabih Berri,
and will make a speech at the Superior School of Business in
Beirut, a Franco-Lebanese joint institution established in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He will also re-open the restored historical site of the French
embassy in Beirut, the Residence des Pins, which was abandoned by
France in 1982 during the invasion of Lebanon by Israeli troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
