<HEADLINE> Australian Sharemarkets Ends Higher After Afternoon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares enjoyed a rare
afternoon surge to close one percent higher Thursday after buying
interest was revived by a recovery on the Hong Kong market.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 27.6 points firmer at 2714.6.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index gained 56.9 to 4722.6 and the all
resources put up 2.4 to 1101.0.
</P>
<P>
Brokers attributed the rise to the revival in the Hong Kong
market in the afternoon and the implications that held for Wall
Street Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Dicksons broker Jon Hancock said : " the expectation here is
now that the U.S. market will rise strongly tonight."
</P>
<P>
The local main index started the day up 6.6 points and was up
only 5.4 points by midday.
</P>
<P>
The strength in the local share market was reflected among most
of the majors with particularly strong rises in the News Corp
shares, banks, retailers and some building materials companies.
</P>
<P>
News Corp ordinary shares ended 28 cents higher and the
preferred shares gained 17.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
Banking shares also made strong gains with the sub-index up
86.8 points at 5899.0.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank rose 40.4 cents, ANZ climbed 32,
Commonwealth firmed 29 and Westpac grew 13.8 cents.
</P>
<P>
Retailer Woolworths jumped 17 cents on expectations that retail
sales figures due out on Monday will be positive.
</P>
<P>
BHP closed four cents higher at 13.54 Australian dollars. Rio
Tinto firmed 15, WMC climbed 0.7.
</P>
<P>
The gold index lost 22 points to 1182.6. Gold stocks defied the
1.30 U.S. dollar rise in bullion to 293.50 an ounce to close.
</P>
<P>
Overall 302.3 million shares changed hands worth 904.6 million
Australian dollars (560.85 million U.S. dollars). Falling stocks
shaded rising stocks by 632 to 556. 
</P>
</TEXT>
