<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Holds FMs Council Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The half-yearly meeting of NATO
council of foreign ministers, held here Thursday, is to focus on
Kosovo and the new strategic concept of the western military bloc.
</P>
<P>
NATO is considering sending peacemaking troops to northern
Albania to help fend off possible spillover into the Balkan nation
of the turmoil in neighboring Yugoslavia's province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers are to discuss options ranging from
minimum to maximum assistance to the Balkan country via sending
NATO-led troops consisting from 7,000 to 22,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Italy and some Scandinavian nations have expressed willingness
to join the NATO peacemaking force. Italy joined a NATO force to
assist Albania in calming down a domestic unrest early last year.
</P>
<P>
A NATO official, who asked not to be named, said the meeting
will send out an "important signal that NATO is interested in the
unstable region of the Balkans" and it will be there if needed.
</P>
<P>
Whether NATO should wait for a mandate from the United Nations
Security Council is the key issue in the decision-making process
of this two-day ministerial meeting.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the meeting said France insists that a
U.N. mandate is a must for any NATO action in the Balkans whereas
the United States, Britain, Italy, Turkey and Canada opposed the
U.N. route and wanted to have a free hand for potential NATO move.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers will also meet their counterparts from
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic, Russia, Ukraine and from
the member states of the Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council.
</P>
<P>
The NATO-Russia Permanent Joint Council is expected to discuss
nuclear non-proliferation and transparency and
military-to-military cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
