<HEADLINE> Tibet Economy Grows by 13.2 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region in
southwest China recorded a GDP (gross domestic product) of 7.698
billion yuan last year, a rise of 13.2 percent over the previous
year, according to the regional statistics bureau.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate was 7.4 percentage points higher than the
region's average for the previous five years and also much higher
than the national economic growth rate of 8.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan economy has been growing at a two-digit rate for
four consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
During the past five years, Tibet invested 14.1 billion yuan in
expanding fixed assets, mostly in capital construction and
infrastructure projects, laying a solid foundation for the
economic surge. The figure more than doubled that for the previous
five years.
</P>
<P>
Tibet also produced 791,900 tons of grain last year, the 10th
consecutive year of good agricultural harvests.
</P>
<P>
The bureau also reported an improvement in local people's
living standard. Last year, the per capita income was 1,085 yuan
for farmers and 5,135 yuan for urban residents. About 270,000 out
of the 480,000 impoverished people were able to rise above the
poverty line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
