<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of India's Economic Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Following are highlights of the
1997-98 Economic Survey tabled Thursday before the Indian
Parliament by the Ministry of Finance:
</P>
<P>
-- Immediate policy decisions required to ensure macro-economic
stability and rapid and sustainable growth to ward off effects of
sanctions on India.
</P>
<P>
-- Gross Domestic Product growth decelerated to 5 percent from
7.5 percent in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
-- Gross domestic saving and gross domestic investment recorded
at 26.1 and 27.3 percent of the GDP in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
-- Average inflation rate in 1997-98 was less than 5 percent
compared to 6.3 percent in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
-- Foodfrain production in 1997-98 was estimated at 194.1
million tones as against 199.3 million tones last year.
</P>
<P>
-- Industrial production grew by 4.2 percent in 1997-98
compared to 7.1 percent in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
-- Credit growth continues to be low because of weak demand for
credit as banks adopted cautious approach to lending.
</P>
<P>
-- Process of fiscal consolidation received setback in 1997-98
with government fiscal deficit reaching 6.1 percent of GDP as
against budget target of 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- Current account deficit is expected to be about 1.5 percent
of GDP. Export growth decelerated further to 2.6 percent in
1997-98 from 5.3 percent last year and import growth declined from
6.7 percent in 1996-97 to 5.8 percent in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
-- External debt declined to about 24 percent of GDP in
September 1997 from about 26 percent in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
-- Key challenges for economic policy formulation include
revival of agriculture, industrial and export growth, containing
fiscal deficit and development of physical and human
infrastructure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
