<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Painful Adjustment to Make Hong Kong Healthier: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive of the
Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa said Thursday
that the current economic adjustment, which is painful and may
last longer, was a good thing for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"This is a necessary correction for us to move ahead and be
competitive again and to regain our economic vitality," Tung told
economists here Thursday at a conference jointly organized by the
International Institute for Strategic Studies and Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
In a question-and-answer session, the Hong Kong leader said
that Hong Kong was going through a period of structural adjustment
because years of high property prices, a negative interest rate,
and high inflation and wages had created a bubble.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian financial turmoil accelerated this correction," said
the Chief Executive, who admitted that the process could be
painful and prolonged.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed: "The adjustment is a good thing for Hong
Kong. I think after the adjustment period we will be much
healthier and better." Tung said he could not give a timetable for
a full recovery of Hong Kong economy before uncertainties in Asia
went away. But he was confident that Hong Kong would benefit from
China's economic expansion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
