<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Woos Foreign Funds for Building Materials Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- China has introduced five billion
U.S. dollars in overseas funds into its building materials
industry and is trying to attract even more.
</P>
<P>
The funds will be used to produce new building materials,
inorganic nonmetallic materials, and equipment to manufacture
building materials, according to a senior official with the State
Administration of Building Materials, which is asking overseas
enterprises involved to strictly abide by Chinese laws and rules
and to meet industry needs and provide advice.
</P>
<P>
The official said the use of overseas funds should take the
industry's product mix restructuring into consideration as well as
environmental protection. All overseas-funded projects must meet
international standards for environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Overseas funds will be introduced mainly for producing cement,
glass and ceramics. The country is encouraging the undertaking of
large cement projects and technology upgrading in small cement
plants. In cement production, the focus will be placed on
improving product quality.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Building Materials will also set
ceilings on overseas-funded enterprises, and will not allow the
establishment of wholly foreign-owned cement and glass
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Co-funded technological transformation or share-holding by
foreigners in key state-owned enterprises, whose products are
listed in the country's production plans, will be allowed only
with approval from government departments.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, overseas-funded projects should pay attention to
technical upgrading. China particularly encourages the
establishment of research and development centers for glass
fiber-reinforced plastic and other new building materials for the
sustained development of related technology.
</P>
<P>
Production equipment in overseas-funded cement, glass, and
ceramics enterprises should be purchased through bidding and at
least 50 percent of the equipment should be domestic, according to
the administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
