<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman on Netanyahu's Visit to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The visit to China by Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyaha took place at a critical time in the
development of the Middle East peace process, Chinese Foreign
Ministry Spokesman Zhu Bangzao said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese and Israeli leaders had an exchange of views with
emphasis on how to push forward the Middle East peace talks," he
said in the routine news briefing.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Chinese side expressed candidly its concern
over the current stalemate of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The key to breaking the deadlock is to earnestly implement the
agreements reached between the Israeli and Arab sides in
compliance with relevant UN resolutions and the principle of "Land
for Peace," he said, emphasizing that only when a comprehensive
and just peace is realized in the Middle East, will the region,
including Israel, enjoy genuine security.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the Israeli side will size up the
situation, respond to the calls of the international community
and adopt a more flexible attitude, so as to push the peace talks
out of the dilemma and facilitate ensuring progress.
</P>
<P>
"China will, as always, make unremitting effort to this end," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu, Netanyahu briefed the Chinese side on Israel's
contacts with the United States and other parties concerned. He
thanked the Chinese side for its concern over the cause of the
peace in the Middle East and hoped that China would play a greater
role in promoting the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Also, Zhu said that leaders of the two countries also exchanged
views on bilateral relations and international issues of
common interest. Both sides expressed willingness to further
strengthen cooperation on the basis of equality and mutual
benefit.
</P>
<P>
"No agreement on bilateral cooperation was signed during the
visit," Zhu said.  
</P>
