<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Israeli Soldiers Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Two Israeli soldiers were killed
and two others wounded in south Lebanon overnight by a Lebanese
guerrillas' roadside bomb, Lebanon's Voice of the People radio
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bomb exploded when an Israeli armored patrol passed on a
road leading to the village of Marka inside the Israeli occupied
security zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed
responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
The new casualties brought to six the number of Israeli
soldiers killed in south Lebanon since the start of 1998. Last
year, 39 Israeli soldiers were killed in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese security sources said Israeli troops would soon
launch a harsh military offensive in retaliation for Hezbollah's
attack.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah is leading a guerrilla war in south Lebanon in a
bid to drive the 2,000 Israeli soldiers from the country.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its northern
areas from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
But the heavy losses Israel has suffered in the area have
forced the Israeli government to think about ways of leaving
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel has offered to withdraw from south Lebanon under the
condition that Lebanon grants border security before Israeli
troops pullout.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its ally Syria have rejected the offer, insisting
that Israel must leave Lebanon as stipulated in the United
Nations Resolution 425, which calls for an unconditional and
immediate Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which has 40,000 troops deployed in Lebanon, seeks a
comprehensive deal which would also involve an Israeli withdrawal
from the Golan Heights, captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle
East war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
