<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Govt Tries to Ward off Effects of Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government prescribed
immediate policy initiatives Thursday to try to ward off adverse
effects of sanctions imposed by the United States, Japan and other
countries following India's nuclear tests earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
In the 1997-98 Economic Survey tabled before the Parliament
today, the government said it was too early to comment on the
implications of the sanctions, both short and medium term, for the
Indian economy as some countries reacted negatively to its nuclear
tests.
</P>
<P>
It was imperative to implement the policy decisions necessary
to ensure macroeconomics stability and rapid and sustainable
economic growth of 7 to 8 percent, said the survey prepared by the
Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
India's overall economic growth rate has decelerated
significantly to 5 percent in 1997-98 from 7.5 percent in 1996-97
and its trade deficit widened by a whopping 6.6 billions U.S.
dollars despite a sharp decline in imports which grew at a rate of
5.8 percent in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
The sharp slowdown in Gross Domestic Product (GDP) and export
growth, which the survey attributed mainly to the sharp fall in
growth rate in agriculture and industry, were identified as two
central areas of concern besides slippages on the fiscal front
during 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
Concern about fiscal deficit and infrastructure problems
continue to rise with each passing year and higher growth is the
best antidote for removing mass poverty and unemployment and for
generating revenues needed to supply goods and other government
services.
</P>
<P>
The task of preserving macroeconomic stability was complicated
by the lack of fiscal flexibility, the survey said, adding that
the fiscal deficit had reached 6.1 percent of GDP as against
targeted 4.5 percent in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
The deceleration in the rate of inflation from the beginning of
the year reflected moderate money supply growth, sluggish demand,
abundant agricultural supplies and high production in 1996-97 and
competitive price discipline in an increasingly open economy.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that the balance of payment situation in
1997-98 remained sound and the current account deficit was
expected to be about 1.5 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The survey admitted that the process of fiscal correction
received a serious setback during 1997-98 largely on account of a
shortfall in tax collections and disinvestments receipts.
</P>
<P>
There was a need to persevere in the process of prudent fiscal
management, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
