<HEADLINE> 1 Million Australians Use Internet at Home: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- One in every 18 Australians, or 1
million Australian residents, used the Internet at home early this
year, compared with 250,000 two years earlier, the Australian
Bureau of Statistics said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the bureau, householders were
still reluctant to buy over Internet, with only about 207,000
people having made private purchases online in the 12 months to
February, and only 170,000 paying online.
</P>
<P>
"Only 44,000 persons are estimated to have used the Internet to
pay other bills or transfer funds in the last three months," the
bureau said in its "Use of the Internet by Householders."
</P>
<P>
The total number of personal computers in Australia is
estimated at 6.9 million.
</P>
<P>
The bureau also found about 3 million Australians aged 18 years
or older had used the Internet in the 12 months to February; 1.3
million from work, 1 million from home and 1.5 million from a
friend or neighbor's house, a school or university or a public
library.
</P>
<P>
Having created an Information Economy Ministry to oversee the
Internet and information industries last year, the Australian
government has been encouraging the use of Internet and electronic
commerce by government departments, business and individuals in a
bid to improve efficiency and competitiveness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
