<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Ready to Deploy Arrow-2 Missile System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Defense Ministry has
approved a missile defense plan for the next decade, paving the
way for the deployment of the Arrow-2 anti-ballistic missile
system, the Jerusalem Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai Wednesday convened top
Israeli military commanders and defense officials for a meeting
and approved a multi-year defense plan to develop and produce the
Homa (Wall) anti-missile system, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Homa program launched in the 1980s mainly includes the two
Arrow-2 anti-missile batteries with their Green Pine
missile-tracking radar and Citron Tree fire-control system.
</P>
<P>
The program, which was estimated to cost about 1.6 billion
U.S. dollars, is largely financed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Air Force Commander Maj.-Gen. Eitan Ben-Eliahu said in
the meeting that the air force was preparing to deploy the first
Arrow-2 battery and scheduled to finish the deployment of the
second battery by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
And the Arrow-2 missile's Green Pine radar has been put into
operation, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has promised to fund Israel's research and development
of the third Arrow battery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Level Declines in New Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Compounding the unbearable heat
and frequent cut of power supply, the Indian capital of New Delhi
is facing a severe shortage of water.
</P>
<P>
Water has already become precious in many parts of the city,
and the Statesman newspaper reported Thursday that it will become
one of the rarest commodities in a couple of years as all the
underground sources of water are drying up at an alarming pace.
</P>
<P>
The Underground water level in the capital is going down at an
average of 0.4 meters every year, according to a recent study
conducted by the hydrologists at the Nuclear Research Laboratory
(NRL) of the Indian Agricultural Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
In the southern part of New Delhi, the underground water level
has plummeted from 15 meters below the ground in 1979 to 20 meters
in 1984 and 29 meters in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In the northern part, the underground water level has fallen
appreciably from three meters in 1984 to 10 meters in 1989 and 25
meters in 1994, said the study.
</P>
<P>
This would severely affect the life of the inhabitants because
more than 70 percent of the population of around 10 million in the
capital are dependent on the underground sources of water.
</P>
<P>
NRL principal scientist Dr. P. S. Dutta, leader of the
research, attributed the phenomenon to the rapid urbanization.
</P>
<P>
There is hardly any open space left for rain water, the only
source of underground water, to percolate below the soil due to
concrete construction in every part of the city. And in most parts
of the city, only 5 percent of rain water actually permeates below
the ground, he explained.
</P>
<P>
The problem has been further aggravated by the improper
drainage system which makes the rain water impossible to be
stored.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say that the only solution before the authorities
and citizens to the water problem at the moment is to make prudent
use of this priceless natural resource.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Minister Unseated for Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's Minister of Labor
and Youth Development, Sebastian Kinyondo, has lost his
parliamentary seat after he was charged with corruption and use
of abusive language against others in his 1995 election
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
The High Court Wednesday unseated Kinyondo as the parliament
member for Bukoba Rural constituency by the Lake Victoria, by
declaring his 1995 parliamentary election results null and void,
Dar es Salaam newspapers said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The nullification means that Kinyondo automatically loses his
ministerial post.
</P>
<P>
The Registrar of the High Court in Bukoba, Daniel Safari, said
that the court was convinced that Kinyondo, a member of the
ruling party Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM), had used defamatory
language during his campaigns against Medard Mutungi who
contested for the seat as a CHADEMA candidate.
</P>
<P>
The High Court found Kinyondo "guilty" by claiming that
Mutungi sodomized his schoolmates while studying at the Ihungo
Secondary School.
</P>
<P>
Kinyondo was also charged with bribing women groups with
clothes and offering wine and various drinks to other voters
during the 1995 campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Mutungi has also claimed that Kinyondo and his agents bribed
the returning officer with alcohol and managed to open ballot
boxes at will and inserted votes in favor of Kinyondo.
</P>
<P>
In his 120-page ruling, Judge Kahwa Rugakingira ordered
Kinyondo to pay all costs of the petition which was filed by
Mutungi asking the court to nullify the election results. Under
the ruling, Kinyondo is barred from contesting parliamentary seat
for the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Kinyondo, absent from the court, is reportedly on a trip in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
In the 1995 election results, Kinyondo scooped 42,169 votes, while
Mutungi won 10,116 votes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
