<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong 12-day-old Baby Makes Medical History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 28 (Xinhua) -- A 12-day-old Hong Kong baby has
made medical history to become the world's youngest patient to
take a ground-breaking keyhole surgery in his large intestine.
</P>
<P>
The boy was suffering from total colonic aganglionosis, an
illness that can cause fatal bowel obstruction for lack of nerve
cells in the large intestine. He was diagnosed two days after
birth.
</P>
<P>
The 2.7 kg infant has successfully undergone a laparoscopic, or
 keyhole surgery, in which surgeons inserted a thin tube with a
light and camera into the body. The affected section of the large
intestine was cut and removed during the three-hour operation
which took place on May 5 at Prince of Wales Hospital attached to
the Chinese University of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in the world that a laparoscopic surgery
was conducted in so young a baby in a single operation. In the
past, only older patients take such operations, which had to be
completed in three separate stages.
</P>
<P>
About one in 5,000 children suffers from the colonic
aganglionosis in Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Destroys Illicit Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has destroyed 500,000 U.S.
Dollars worth of illicit drugs recently, official with the
National Drug Authority (NDA) has said.
</P>
<P>
Abbas Kalogo, the NDA Executive Secretary, was quoted as
saying at a one-day seminar on drugs for media-practitioners in
Kampala that local, international security agencies and Uganda
Revenue Authority have assisted in the massive fight against the
harmful drugs.
</P>
<P>
"These drugs have been destroyed at the supplier's or
importer's expenses. Uganda is no longer a dumping ground for
harmful drugs. Our action has been very stringent," he added.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 90 percent of drugs in Uganda are imported, he noted,
and the NDA's provisional registry has 3,000 drugs for human
beings and more than 300 drugs for animals.
</P>
<P>
To end the country's heavy dependence on foreign drugs, the
authority has spent about 240,000 Dollars to purchase modern
equipment and laboratory facilities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
