<HEADLINE> Mongolian Parliament Approves New Education Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia's top legislature
approved Thursday the appointment of Chimediin Saikhanbileg as the
country's education minister.
</P>
<P>
The confirmation procedure through the Great Hural, or
parliament, therefore accomplished the formation of a new cabinet
staffed with a total of nine ministers.
</P>
<P>
Saikhanbileg, 29, was nominated by Prime Minister Tsakhya
Elbegdorj as the fifth candidate for the post, after the other
four nominees were turned down by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
He would be the youngest education minister in the country's
history, said the information office of the Great Hural.
</P>
<P>
Saikhanbileg graduated from the Department of History at the
Moscow Institute of Youth in 1991 and then the Law School of the
Mongolian State University in 1995.
</P>
<P>
A member of the Mongolian National Democratic Party, he was
elected into the Great Hural on June 1996, and has been Chairman
of the Mongolian Youth Union since 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
