<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1997: A Boom Year for Philanthropy in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Americans gave more than 140
billion U.S. dollar to charities in 1997, up 7.5 percent from
1996, according to a report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of donation by the American people for
philanthropy rose to 143.45 billion dollar thanks to a robust
economy, said the report by the American Association of
Fund-Raising Counsel's Trust for Philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
"This was one of the best years in at least a decade," said Ann
Kaplan, the group's research director. "The last two years have
just been very, very good years."
</P>
<P>
The 1997 rise followed a similar increase in 1996. There was
little or no growth in charitable giving in the early 1990s,
largely as a result of the economic recession.
</P>
<P>
Religious organizations maintained their position at the top of
the charity heap, receiving 74.79 billion dollar, or 6.1 percent
more than 1996.
</P>
<P>
Educational organizations received the second-biggest piece of
the charity pie, netting 21.51 billion dollar, an increase of 12.3
percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Health organizations took the third place, receiving 14.03
billion dollar, up one percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
One area where donations were down was to arts and cultural
organizations, which received 10.62 billion dollar, a decline of
2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The statistics in the report are based on deductible
contributions listed on tax returns and surveys of givers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
