<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Opposition Leaders Attacked, Says Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Investigations conducted by human
rights watch into last year's shooting in Kabwe, Zambia, have
revealed that former President Kenneth Kaunda and another
opposition leader were shot at.
</P>
<P>
At an opposition gathering held in Kabwe, 150 kilometers north
of Lusaka, Kanuda, leader of the country's largest opposition
United National Independence Party (UNIP), and Rodger Chongwe who
heads Liberal Progressive Front were allegedly shot at by police,
the country's leading independent newspaper, The Post, reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda's forehead was reportedly scratched while Chongwe was
seriously injured in the shooting. But the Zambian government has
denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a Human Rights Watch report for May 1998 as
saying that the bullet hole in Kaunda's vehicle, a bullet
catridge found at the scene of the incident and the bullet
reportedly taken from the car show that the vehicle was hit.
</P>
<P>
If the shrapnel had hit him a couple of inches to the left,
Kaunda would have been dead, according to the report which came
after a detailed ballistic analysis of the Kabwe incident
conducted with the help of Richard Shepherd of the forensic
medical unit at St. George's Hospital school in London.
</P>
<P>
The Human Rights Watchdog urged the Zambian government to
support an independent inquiry into the shooting and publish the
results and make those responsible for human rights abuses
accountable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
