<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Loan Disbursement to Indonesia Not Decided </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- An official of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) said here Thursday that he will soon report on
the latest situation in Indonesia to enable the fund to decide
when to release the one-billion-U.S.-dollar loan as part of its
rescue package for the country.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the IMF loan would be disbursed as soon as possible.
But I have not reached the final stage of my assessment," IMF
director for Asia Pacific, Hubert Neiss told the press after
meeting with President B. J. Habibie here.
</P>
<P>
Neiss said that since he just arrived last Wednesday, he was
still holding meetings with both Indonesian government officials
and public figures.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on Indonesia's economic situation, Neiss said
Indonesia's macroeconomy is weaker than in the past few months,
thus needing many recovery efforts, particularly in the financial
sector.
</P>
<P>
He said the IMF is ready to cooperate with the new government's
economic team, especially in implementing the IMF-recommended
economic reform program.
</P>
<P>
He added that during their one-hour meeting, Habibie explained
to him the government's plans to strengthen the economy, mainly by
putting pressure on the inflation rate and boosting economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
In October last year, the IMF expressed its readiness to extend
funds worth 10 billion U.S. dollars to help revive the ailing
Indonesian economy.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank also promised to pitch in 4.5 billion dollars,
the Asian Development Bank 3.5 billion dollars, and the Indonesian
government itself 5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some countries have also expressed their commitment to
extending a total assistance of 20 billion dollars, under both the
framework of the IMF and bilateral terms.
</P>
<P>
The IMF released the first tranche of loan amounting to 3
billion dollars in November last year. It promised to extend the
next 3 billion dollars in the three months from May to July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
