<HEADLINE> Three Feared Dead in Nairobi Downpour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Three people were feared drowned
after Nairobi River burst its banks following a heavy downpour in
the Kenyan capital Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said they died after being swept away by the
torrents while they were trying to cross the swelling river at a
bridge.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper Thursday quoted police as saying
that the Nairobi River also swept away two matatus (mini-buses)
full of passengers, adding that the fate of the passengers still
unknown.
</P>
<P>
The city was paralyzed for hours in the reportedly historic
downpour which began at 5:30 p.m. local time at the height of the
evening rush hour and continued unabated until 10:30 p.m..
</P>
<P>
At least five cars were reported swept away and hundreds of
houses submerged in different parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
Even President Daniel arap Moi was caught up in the traffic
jam Wednesday evening. He surprised staff and guests at the New
Stanley Hotel in downtown when he popped in and took shelter.
</P>
<P>
The downpour, which was accompanied by thunderstorm, threw
evening traffic into chaos and left many commuters stranded and
drenched with rain at many bus stops. Hundreds of workers walked
home after a futile wait for vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Bars and restaurants experienced an upsurge in business as
hundreds of residents poured in, waiting for traffic to clear.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, a hailstorm hit the city, causing a lot of
damage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
