<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Causes, Suggested Solutions for Unemployment Problem (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The large number of redundant
workers, the transformation of economic systems, the adjustment of
industrial structure, and the speeding up of the urbanization
process were listed by a newspaper article today as the main causes
for the emergence of laid-off workers from state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The "People's Daily" carried a lengthy article expounding the
causes for the large-scale layoffs at state-owned enterprises and
suggested that the idea of trying to eliminate total unemployment
should be abandoned and the whole society needs to take care of
the re-employment project; get a correct idea of employment;
enlarge employment channels; and improve related policies.
</P>
<P>
The existence of the large number of surplus workers in
state-owned enterprises is the basic cause for the phenomenon,
the article emphasized, adding that under the structure of a
planning economy, employment comes by administrative arrangement,
which is similar to a welfare system.
</P>
<P>
With the deepening reform of state-owned enterprises, the
number of workers to be laid off from the surplus work force must
increase by a large margin, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Under the investment structure of a planned economy,
overlapping constructions have wasted limited resources. With the
rapid adjustment of the industrial structure, some enterprises
must be merged or eliminated through competition, which will
result in a large number of laid-off workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Causes, Suggested Solutions for Unemployment Problem (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The idea of "eliminating unemployment in a socialist society"
is an employment idea for an agricultural society, which must be
changed in a modern industrial society, the article stated, adding
that people's viewpoint of employment must be adjusted to cope
with the deepening reform of the economic structure and the social
security systems.
</P>
<P>
The society should develop the service sector and private
industry to enlarge employment channels. The service sector, which
can provide far more employment opportunities than other
industries, constitutes only 24 percent of China's job market
compared to 70 percent of that in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The country's private sector also contributed most, among all
economic sectors, to providing new job opportunities from 1992 to
1996, and the sector also has the broadest prospects for
development, for it only constituted 13 percent of the urban job
market in 1996, compared with 20 percent in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
Family enterprises, urban greenery industry and township
enterprises, which are relatively new industries in China, will
also offer more job opportunities for the society. Besides these
sectors, the adoption of a flexible employment system will be
another plus.
</P>
<P>
A complete set of policies will be worked out to support the
development of the service sector and the private economy, and
preferential policies will also be formulated for workers who
transfer from state-owned enterprises to private or collectively
owned enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN, U.S. Mull Joint Efforts Against Illegal Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) and the United States have agreed to cooperate
more extensively in their common war against illegal drug
production, trafficking and abuse.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency reported Thursday that at the just
concluded ASEAN-U.S. dialogue in Manila, delegates from the two
sides agreed to mobilize their respective agencies in pooled
efforts to more effectively control narcotics trade and abuse.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, a U.S. official said the U.S. is committed
to contributing its share in reducing the illegal drugs traffic
and their abuse in southeast Asia, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Southeast Asia is a confirmed production base of illegal drugs
and where drug abuse is also widespread while the U.S. provides a
huge market for the commodity.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN delegates said a joint ASEAN-U.S. initiative to control
both supply and demand of the illegal commodity is a more
effective strategy.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
Singapore, Thailand, the Philippines and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has been known as a major transshipment point
of the world's illegal drug traffic, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
