<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children Building School From Cola Tins, Toothpaste Tubes (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The idea of collecting cola tins
and toothpaste tubes to build a school sounds unimaginable, but
millions of Chinese children have achieved it following six months
of efforts.
</P>
<P>
China's first environmental elementary school in the suburbs of
Nanchang, capital of east China's Jiangxi Province, was
established today through the collection and sale of penny-worth
wastes.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Children's News, a newspaper influential among
schoolchildren, called on children nationwide at the end of 1996
to raise money through waste collection to build an elementary
school for poor children in Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
By July of 1997, the newspaper office had received more than
243,000 yuan from children across the country, including Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"More than 2,000 pupils at our school collected over 85,000
pieces of wastes, packing nine trucks, and selling for some 8,000
yuan (1,000 US dollars)," said Yu Miao, a sixth-grade student at
Yucai Elementary School in Wuhan, capital of central China's Hubei
Province.
</P>
<P>
"We want to do something for the cleaning of the earth and also
for our poor pals in Jiangxi," Yu said.
</P>
<P>
Taohua Village in Nanchang's northern suburb had a school,
which was only a row of worn-out single-story house, before a new
one was built.
</P>
<P>
Local pupils said: "We could see stars from the classroom, and
would freeze when winter came."
</P>
<P>
The newly built four-story school undoubtedly has brought hope
to local children. Relevant government departments have decided to
designate the school as the country's first environmental
education base for children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
