<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children Building School from Cola Tins, Toothpaste Tubes (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lu Qing, Chinese children's "intimate sister" and the deputy
editor-in-chief of the Chinese Children's News, said: "The school,
which was built from cola tins and toothpaste tubes, is a great
gift from Chinese children both to the upcoming International
Children's Day on June 1 and the World Environmental Day on June
5."
</P>
<P>
She added that the move has enabled children to see that they
can do great things through unity, and fostered their
environmental awareness of "turning the useless into the useful."
</P>
<P>
"Children are a force that should not be neglected in
implementing the basic state policy of environmental protection,"
Lu said.
</P>
<P>
China has opened environmental classes in elementary and middle
schools, and tried to foster children's ability to probe and
understand environmental problems as well as searching for ways to
solve them in education, she said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, many student environmental organizations like the
"earth village" have been set up in schools nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The State Environmental Protection Administration and the
National Working Committee of the Young Pioneers have decided to
establish 2,000 "Hand-in-hand Earth Villages" across the country
within two years. These student organizations will conduct regular
environmental activities.  
</P>
