<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Succeeds in Making Pomegranate Wine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, May 28 (Xinhua) -- A small business in northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region has added a new variety
-- pomegranate wine -- to the wine family in the country.
</P>
<P>
After two years of research, the China Hotan Rose Wine Industry
Co., Ltd., in Hotan Prefecture of southern Xinjiang, began brewing
the new wine early this year, which made its debut recently and
met immediate market recognition, said the company's general
manager Wang Jianjun.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture produces nearly 3,000 tons of pomegranates
annually, sufficient for 1,000 tons of pomegranate wine. Wang
predicted a peak time for pomegranate wine production within two
years as local farmers are expanding their pomegranate growing
acreage.
</P>
<P>
The wine sells well in Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou, at a
price of 200-to-400 yuan per bottle, he said.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang has a 2,000-year history of pomegranate plantation,
and the fruit contains twice the amount of vitamins found in
apples and pears. Also, it is rich in such trace elements as
phosphorus, calcium and iron, said Yang Chengshi, a research
fellow with the regional Academy of Agricultural Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Pomegranates have long been used in Uygur medicine for the
treatment of stomach diseases, hypertension and coronary heart
disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
