<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Henan Province to Make Tourism Priority for Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Henan Province in central China
has put forward the idea of making tourism a priority for
development and writing it into the provincial plan for its
economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
A new committee on tourism development and administration, with
a senior provincial official taking charge, will be set up to
intensify tourism construction and development, said local sources.
</P>
<P>
The local governments at various levels will be urged to
include investment for tourism into their annual budgets and to
earmark special funds for tourism in tandem with the original 12
million yuan of special financial allocation set aside by the
provincial government.
</P>
<P>
The province has also encouraged the state, collective and
individual, as well as overseas investors, to explore local
tourism resources in its various forms.
</P>
<P>
In the near future Henan, commonly considered the "birthplace
of the Chinese nation and culture," will concentrate its efforts
on constructing four major tourist routes which feature ancient
cultures along the Yellow River, pilgrimages, martial arts and
specialized research.
</P>
<P>
Li Chenyu, executive deputy governor, emphasized that the main
task of tourism in the future will be to improve existing tourist
sites and related services instead of building more new tourist
sites.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that the province would redouble efforts to expand
the international tourism market. While continuing to keep and
develop its tourism market in Japan, Southeast Asia, and Hong
Kong, Macao and Taiwan, the province will vigorously expand
tourism markets in the Republic of Korea (ROK), Europe, America
and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province attracted 46.264 million tourists,
including 264,000 overseas visitors, and earned about 27.78
billion yuan from tourism industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
