<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Develops Weevil-Resistant Peas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Australia has produced
genetically-modified peas almost 100 percent resistant to weevils,
the most damaging pest of the nation's pea crop.
</P>
<P>
Dr. T. J. Higgins with the Commonwealth Scientific and
Industrial Research Organization (CSIRO), a leading research body
in Australia, made the announcement at a science briefing on gene
technology in Canberra Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Currently, growers spend up to 16 million Australian dollars
(about 10 million U.S. dollars) a year on chemical insecticides to
control the pea weevils," said Higgins.
</P>
<P>
"In our field trials, we've shown that the genetically-modified
peas are 99.5 percent resistant to weevil attack, no insecticide
required," he said.
</P>
<P>
Higgins said his research team introduced into the peas a gene
found in the common kidney bean which has a natural resistance to
those seed-eating weevils.
</P>
<P>
"This gene produces a protein that blocks the normal digestion
of seed contents by weevil larvae, so they don't grow and develop
into adults."
</P>
<P>
"Weevils can reduce yields by 25 to 30 percent," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tests in four of Australia's six states show the
genetically-modified peas are identical to conventional peas in
every way except in their susceptibility to insect attack, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The researchers will attempt to apply the same method to other
important food legumes such as chickpeas and cowpeas.
</P>
<P>
Weevils are particularly severe in Asia, Africa and South
America, Higgins said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Anti-desert Project Under Way in Qinghai Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Golmud City on the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau is fighting to avoid being engulfed by desertification.
</P>
<P>
The 146-million-yuan (17.59 million U.S. dollars)
anti-desertification project is designed to plant 7,272.2 hectares
of vegetation, and establish standardized plant nurseries,
botanical gardens of cold-resistant plants, wind-break tree belts,
and a huge water conservation project in eight years.
</P>
<P>
Due to influence of geographic and weather conditions, Golmud
is susceptible to wind erosion. The situation has been made worse
with the process of industrialization and random tree felling.
</P>
<P>
According to incomplete statistics, 1.33 million hectares of
vegetation in the city has been destroyed in the past decades,
leaving more than 3.8 million hectares of desert for the city.
</P>
<P>
The local as well as Qinghai provincial governments have always
attached great importance to anti-desertification efforts, local
authorities said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
