<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction of New Rail Line Starts Today in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a railway involving
loans from the Asian Development Bank started today in northwest
China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The 385-kilometer rail line will link Yan'an City, which
is known as the "cradle of the Chinese revolution," and Shenmu
City, all in northern Shaanxi. Total cost of the rail line, which
is scheduled to be completed in 2001, is estimated at 6.74
billion yuan (780 million U.S. dollars), including 200 million
U.S. dollars in loans from the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The north-south line will run through major coal and natural
gas fields in Shaanxi and will connect with major railways of the
province and eventually form another north-south trunk line in
western China that will run parallel with the Beijing-Guangzhou
and Beijing-Kowloon railways.
</P>
<P>
Because of complicated topographical conditions, the construction
will include 22 major bridges and 27 tunnels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
