<HEADLINE> Australian Wheat Output Predicted to Jump Markedly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Australian wheat farmers will see
their best crop production season in a decade with predictions of
a 22-percent increase to 16 million tons in production this year
because of weather pattern changes, Australian experts said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Australian climatologist Roger Stone said the sudden rise in
the Southern Oscillation Index (SOI), which measures water
temperatures in the Coral Sea to the northeast of Australia
indicated the El Nino dry weather influence was decaying.
</P>
<P>
"This year is shaping up to be one of the best for Australian
wheat farmers and other grain and cotton growers since the 1980s
with improving chances of good rainfall over much of the
continent," Stone told a climate workshop for agricultural
officials and rural representatives in Brisbane, capital of
Australia's Queensland state.
</P>
<P>
Holger Meinke, a crop output analyst, said Australia could
produce an extra 3 million tons of wheat worth 260 million U.S.
dollars this season.
</P>
<P>
Australia's wheat crop totals 16 million tons in a "fair"
season, the Australian Associated Press said.
</P>
<P>
"Based on rainfall probabilities, growers can manage for a
record crop, an opportunity that does not occur often," Meinke
said.
</P>
<P>
Stone, senior climatologist at Queensland's Center for Climate
Applications, said a further boost for wheat farmers were
indications of adverse growing conditions among Australia's major
competitors including the United States, Argentina and Central
America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
