<HEADLINE> Famous Tourism Site in Beijing Closed to Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The administrative office of the
Summer Palace, in Beijing's western outskirts, has fenced up the
Marble Boat and closed it to visitors to prevent further damage.
</P>
<P>
The 36-meter-long Marble Boat beside Kunming Lake in the
western portion of the Summer Palace, was first built in 1755. It
survived a fire in 1860 and was rebuilt in 1893.
</P>
<P>
The Marble Boat attracts thousands of visitors every
year. However, its wooden pavilion in western architectural style
suffers serious erosion from wind and rain, and the carvings on
the boat suffer from wear and tear by visitors.
</P>
<P>
The administrative office announced plans to repair the boat
next year.
</P>
<P>
The Summer Palace, close to the Western Hills, was built by the
Dowager Empress of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) to celebrate her
60th birthday with funds collected to build a navy.
</P>
<P>
The park itself covers 823 acres with more than 100 buildings
-- halls, towers, pavilions, bridges, pagodas and the richly
painted 1,500-meter Long Corridor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
