<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Phone Company to Offer High-Speed Internet Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Pacific Bell, a subsidiary
local telephone company of SBC Communications, announced Wednesday
that it plans to offer high-speed Internet service this summer.
</P>
<P>
The service, to be available to more than a third of its
customers across California, will use existing phone lines and
move data at up to 30 times faster than today's computer modems.
</P>
<P>
Behind the new service is a new technology known as asymmetric
digital subscriber line, or ADSL, which is designed primarily for
Internet and telecommuting, namely home office, applications.
</P>
<P>
Packaged with Internet service, ADSL provides on-line consumers
and small businesses with accelerated access to the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
In addition, as a stand-alone connection, ADSL allows
telecommuting employees and after-hours home workers to connect
their employers' corporate networks via dedicated, secure links.
</P>
<P>
Pacific Bell had been moving cautiously to deploy the new
technology in its service area covering over 13.4 million business
and residential customers.
</P>
<P>
After a year-long test and a lengthy market trial, it plans to
charge home users 89 U.S. dollars per month and businesses up to
339 dollars per month for the service, including Internet access.
</P>
<P>
The company already offers the high-speed service in parts of
the San Francisco Bay Area, with monthly prices ranging from about
160 dollars to 400 dollars.
</P>
<P>
To be eligible for the new service, users must be within about
5 kilometers of one of its offices in 63 cities. The deployment
will start expanding in June, company officials said, and should
be finished by late August or September.
</P>
<P>
To use ADSL technology, a new modem would be required, and the
phone company would need to install new equipment. Once installed,
ADSL is always on and consumers would never need to dial their
Internet service provider again. Also, people can talk on the
phone and surf the Web at the same time on the same line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
