<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Export of Labor Services Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- After two decades of development,
China's export of labor services has continuously improved in the
past few years with the implementation of a quality strategy,
according to an official with China's Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
More and more specialists such as engineers, doctors, nurses
and certified accountants as well as high-tech and business
management personnel in aircraft maintenance, computer software
development and applications, project designing, consulting and
management are working abroad, said Cui Mingmo, deputy director
of the Department of Foreign Economic Cooperation of
MOFTEC.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the number of laborers involved in such
services abroad reached 1.54 million.
</P>
<P>
When China started such services at the end of the '70s after
it initiating a reform and opening-up policy, its export of labor
services only involved ordinary workers and technicians, Cui said.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has established and applied a training
system for contract workers sent abroad, which would enable them
to learn about the country, local laws and customs.
</P>
<P>
The trained workers were well received by both domestic and
overseas companies, and such a system has laid a solid foundation
for an expected further improvement of such workers and businesses
in China, Cui said.
</P>
<P>
The labor services for overseas projects have also helped some
state-owned large- and medium-size enterprises deal with their
redundant workers and expand their businesses, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some laborers coming from poor areas have earned some money
through working abroad, and some of them even brought information
back to their hometowns for cooperation with overseas partners,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
He quoted a provincial governor as saying that a worker going
abroad can help a whole family be better-off, thus contributing to
the social stability of a locality.
</P>
<P>
He said China will continue to improve the selection,
training and management of such laborers, and MOFTEC will continue
to join diplomatic, public security and industrial and commercial
administrative departments in cracking down on fraudulent
activities in the name of labor services export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exports in Northeastern Industrial Center Picks up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Exports from Shenyang, capital of
northeast China's Liaoning Province, rebounded in the first four
months of this year despite a 7 percent decline compared with a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
Its export value increased from 36.8 million U.S. dollars in
January to 50 million U.S. dollars in March and rose to 67.6
million U.S. dollars in April, according to a Customs Office
report released this week.
</P>
<P>
Exports in general trade decreased by 22 percent at a value of
114 million U.S. dollars in April and that of the processing trade
increased by 24 percent at a value of 90 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang's exports to Asian countries, its traditional market,
declined by 29.5 percent, or 20 million U.S. dollars, in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
But, the city's exports to the United States soared to 24.9
million U.S. dollars, representing a 20 percent rise. Its exports
to Germany increased by 81 percent to 14 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang's exports of nonferrous metal, textiles and garments
decreased by 19.46 million U.S. dollars, or 25.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ling Boshan, a municipal trade official, said the city has to
redouble its efforts and explore more overseas markets before it
can reach its annual export target.  
</P>
</TEXT>
