<HEADLINE> Sampras Crashes Out of French Open in Big Rain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 27 (Xinhua) -- World number one American Pete
Sampras had his Grand Slam sweeping dream all but evaporated as he
crashed out of the French Open here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ten-time Grand Slam winner slumped 7-6, 6-3, 6-4 in
straight sets to little-known Paraguayan Ramon Delgado in a second
round match of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who was the 1996 semifinalist here, could blame his
defeat on the bad weather as the rain fell when he led 4-1 in the
first set.
</P>
<P>
When he returned, the American looked lacking morale, while his
98th-ranked opponent played consistently from the baseline.
</P>
<P>
A passing shot gave the tiebreaker to Delgado, who soon set up
a 3-0 lead in the second set and a 2-0 in the third to hold onto
his upset win.
</P>
<P>
Sampras joined compatriot Andre Agassi and second seed Petr
Korda of the Czech Republic as the early casualties of the event.
</P>
<P>
Agassi fell to Russian sensation Maret Safin on Tuesday and
Korda bowed out to Argentina's Mariano Zabaleta.
</P>
<P>
Third seed Marcelo Rios of Chile stands a real chance of
replacing Sampras again as the world number one.
</P>
<P>
The Chilean showed his domination as he routed Spaniard Emilio
Alvarez 6-4, 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Rios, who became the first ever South American to top the world
rankings last month, meets South African Wayne Ferreira in the
third round.
</P>
<P>
In the women's tournament, Monica Seles saved a first-set loss
to beat South African Marion Maruska 2-6, 6-1, 6-0 in a
second-round tie.
</P>
<P>
World number one Swiss Martina Hingis cruised past German Meike
Babel 6-1, 6-2 in less than one hour, keeping her eyes on the
first title here, while Venus Williams gave more impressive
performance as the eighth-seeded American overwhelmed Japanese Ai
Sugiyama 6-0, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
The two teenager sensations had a potential quarter-final
clash. 
</P>
