<HEADLINE> Cyanide Poisons 580 People in Kirghizstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 27 (Xinhua) -- First Deputy Prime Minister of
Kirghizstan Boris Silayev said Wednesday that up to 580 people
suffered from the leakage of cyanide in the Issyk-Kul state.
</P>
<P>
Silayev, who is also in charge of emergency affairs in the
republic, said 71 of the victims had been hospitalized and another
six in critical condition had been sent to Bishkek, capital of
Kirghizstan, for medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
Silayev blasted Kumtor, a Kirghizstan-Canada joint mining
business, for its delayed report of the accident to the local
government.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred when a truck from Kumtor loaded with
1.5-ton cyanide fell into a river flowing to the lake of
Issyk-Kul. The business reported the incident five hours late.
</P>
<P>
Silayev requested media both home and abroad not to play up the
accident, saying that the leakage would not result in a serious
pollution of the water in Issyk-Kul as only about 200-300
kilograms of cyanide drifted into the lake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
