<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lankan Rebels Step Up Violence in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Tamil rebels have
stepped up violent activities after government forces sought to
intensify their Jaya Sikuru (Certain Victory) operation against
them early this month.
</P>
<P>
Velupillai Prabhakaran, leader of the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam (LTTE), said on May 13 over his clandestine radio
Voice of the Tigers that the rebels would fight to death to defend
their territories.
</P>
<P>
He threatened that thousands of troops would be killed if the
government persisted in pushing ahead with the operation aimed at
capturing a 75-kilometer corridor of a main highway between the
north and the south through rebel-held territories. Government
troops recaptured only 45 kilometers during the course of one
year.
</P>
<P>
The military have declared that the Jaya Sikuru operation will
go on till next year unless another strategy evolves.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has increased its violence not only in the warfront
but also in non-combat areas.
</P>
<P>
On May 14, senior military commander Brigadier Larry Wijeratne
was killed in a suicide bomb attack while on his way to a camp in
the north, just before he was to assume duties as commander of the
Military Academy in Colombo the following week.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the rebels also ambushed an army bus in
Northern Province with claymore mines. They later opened fire on
the soldiers, killing 14 and injuring 35 others.
</P>
<P>
Three days later, a lone gunman shot dead the mayor of a
northern Jaffna town in her home. The rebels had demanded she
relinquish her post or face consequences.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have been opposed to setting up a civil
administration in Jaffna which they claim was their territory but
was recaptured by government troops in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in Sri Lanka this month, LTTE rebels blasted two
electricity transformers in Hatton Town in Central Province,
causing a loss of 16,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE also bombed three separate telecommunication exchanges
at Kuliyapitiya in North-Western Province, Ratnapura in Uva
Province and Nochchiyagama in North-Central Province.
</P>
<P>
The one-and-half-kilogram bomb at Kuliyapitiya caused only
minor damage. But at Nochchiyagama and Ratnapura, telephone
equipment was damaged and all telephones served by these exchanges
were rendered inoperative.
</P>
<P>
Late this month, two squads of LTTE cadres were reported to
have sneaked into the country's capital city, Colombo, to carry
out suicidal bomb attacks, according to Tiger radio transmissions
monitored by the security forces in Trincomalee in the east.
</P>
<P>
They were reported to be targeting two places which are
probably two significant buildings in the city.
</P>
<P>
Security has been tightened in and around Colombo amid fears of
bomb attacks.
</P>
<P>
There has been at least one major bomb attack every month in
Colombo and other key towns since the LTTE blasted the business
center of the capital in October last year.
</P>
<P>
The civil war between the LTTE and government forces has
entered its 15th year and has seen more than 55,000 persons killed
and an even larger number maimed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
