<HEADLINE> Malaysia's New Sabah State Chief Minister Sworn In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Sabah Democratic Party
President Bernard Dompok was sworn in Thursday as the 11th chief
minister of Sabah State, East Malaysia, according to the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Dompok took his oath of office before Yang Dipertua Negeri
(State King) Sakaran Dandai, witnessed by High Court Judge Charles
Ho, at the State Palace in Sabah's capital of Kota Kinabalu, to
replace Yong Teck Lee whose two-year term of office expired
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Yong has been reappointed to the state cabinet but his
portfolio has not been announced, according to Bernama reporting
from Kota Kinabalu.
</P>
<P>
Dompok holds the position to represent the non-Muslim
Bumiputera (aboriginal) community under the rotation system
practiced in the state.
</P>
<P>
Sabah is the only state in Malaysia to practice the rotation
system which has worked well so far as it gives opportunity to all
the three major communities -- Muslim Bumiputeras, the Chinese and
non-Muslim Bumiputeras -- to head the state administration.
</P>
<P>
The rotation system was an election promise by the Barisan
Nasional (National Front) under the leadership of Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad in the 1994 state elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
