<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Local Elections Enter Final Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 28 (Xinhua) -- With the June 4 local elections only
a week away, South Korean political parties have been gearing up
for the final stretch of the election race.
</P>
<P>
Rival political parties, which believe victories are almost
assured in their respective strongholds, are campaigning fiercely
in the election battles waged in Kyonggi and Kangwon provinces.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition of the National Congress for New Politics
(NCNP) and the United Liberal Democrats, is determined to win all
three metropolitan districts -- Seoul, Inchon and Kyonggi, in
which the population accounts for nearly a third of the total
population of the country.
</P>
<P>
The coalition has been going all out to ensure its candidate,
Lim Chang-yuel's victory over Sohn Hak-kyu of the major opposition
Grand National Party (GNP) in the election for the governorship of
Kyonggi province surrounding the capital of Seoul.
</P>
<P>
Park Tae-joon, the ULD president, is to tour Songnam and other
urban areas in Kyonggi this week to seek support for Lim
Chang-yuel, minister of finance and economy of the Kim Young-sam
government.
</P>
<P>
The coalition said it will see its victories in Seoul, where
former Prime Minister Koh Kun of the NCNP is running for mayor,
and in Inchon, where the incumbent mayor Choi Ki-sun is running on
the ULD's ticket.
</P>
<P>
The NCNP is expected to win Cholla and Kwangju regions which
are its traditional political bases while the ULD says it will
surely sweep the Chungchong provinces and Taejon.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the GNP, which controls the 299-member
National Assembly, or parliament, with 161 seats, vowed to win all
five districts in the Kyongsang provinces, Pusan, Taegu and Ulsan,
which are its traditional political strongholds.
</P>
<P>
Although a survey showed its candidates failed to secure solid
leads over independents in Pusan and Ulsan, the GNP said regional
prejudice against the ruling coalition will eventually add up to
overwhelming voter support for its candidates in the two cities.
</P>
<P>
The GNP said its candidate, Sohn Hak-Kyu, has overtaken Lim,
whom it portrayed in TV debates and campaign rallies as one of the
culprits responsible for pushing South Korea into a currency
crisis late last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the GNP noted that it has a great chance to win
Kangwon Province as the ruling coalition's delay in deciding on a
joint candidate split their vote in the province.
</P>
<P>
The NCNP and the ULD failed to produce a joint candidate until
the former gave in shortly before the candidates registration on
May 15. Lee Sang-yong, the former Kangwon governor from whom the
NCNP withdrew its backing, is running as an independent.
</P>
<P>
The minor opposition New Party by the People, with little
chance of winning any of the 15 posts of nine governors and seven
mayors, is trying to win head posts of districts and councils.
</P>
<P>
However, election analysts said the nation will see a record
low turnout rate in the elections as voters become indifferent to
politics because of the ongoing economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
