<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0600 GMT, May 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA -- An International Monetary Fund (IMF) team Wednesday
completed its seven-day review of the Philippine economy, saying
the country had done remarkably well in managing the regional
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
It was the first review by the IMF since the Philippines exited
from the multi-national institution at the end of March this year
after 35 years of tutelage under the IMF.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South Africa's consumer inflation hit a 30-year
low last month when it dropped to five percent year-on-year from
the 5.4 percent in March, according to the statistics released by
the Central Statistical Service (CSS).
</P>
<P>
The fall in inflation was largely due to a one percentage point
drop in home loan rates, from 19 percent in February to 18 percent
in March, newspapers based here Wednesday quoted the CSS
statistics. (S. Africa-inflation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The German economy has begun to profit from a recovery
in domestic demand thanks both to increased investments and
gradually reviving private consumption, a leading German economic
research institute said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
While foreign orders for German investment goods continued to
pour in at "extremely high levels," domestic spendings on
investment goods also registered a strong recovery after a
prolonged recession, the Berlin-based German Institute for
Economic Research DIW said. (Germany-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States Wednesday expressed its
confidence in Russian President Boris Yeltsin's economic team
amid turmoil in the country's financial markets.
</P>
<P>
Russia's leaders are "fully capable" of leading the Russian
economy in the right direction, said State Department spokesman
James Rubin. (US-Russia-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. food agency said Wednesday that the
food situation in most of the Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS) is gradually improving and food aid needs have fallen
sharply.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. Department of Public Information quoted the
U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) as saying that the
CIS continues to have vulnerable groups including pensioners,
disabled people and refugees who cannot afford to buy enough food.
</P>
<P>
The CIS is made up of most of the countries that were once part
of the former USSR.  (UN-CIS Food Production) 
</P>
</TEXT>
