<HEADLINE> Russia Still Against NATO Expansion: Primakov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov said here Wednesday that Russia is still against the
eastward expansion of NATO.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at a joint press conference with his Ukrainian
counterpart, Boris Tarasyuk, after a meeting with Ukrainian
President Leonid Kuchma.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said the expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization would create dangerous factors and new dividing lines
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
If NATO could develop into a political organization and focus
on peace-keeping operations, it would be helpful to promoting its
relationship with Russia, he said.
</P>
<P>
His talks with Kuchma mainly focused on the border issue
between the two countries, relations with NATO, the nuclear tests
in India and the situation in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said the two sides have made "remarkable progress" in
land demarcation.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian foreign minister Tarasyuk said that Ukraine would
stick to its principle on integration with Europe and the
Europe-Atlantic structure.
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign minister arrived in Kiev on Tuesday for a
two-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
