<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Rights Leader Defends Affirmative Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Civil rights gains won in the
1950s-1960s are under attack and progressive groups must combine
forces to fight back, Julian Bond, chairman of the largest
U.S. civil rights group said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We meet at a time when the leadership of the House and Senate
is more hostile to civil rights than in recent memory," Bond, who
is also Chairman of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People (NAACP) said at the National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
Both houses of Congress deserve failing grades on civil rights
matters, said Bond, who was elected chairman of the largest and
oldest civil rights group in the United States in February.
</P>
<P>
The problems are widespread, he said. "Everywhere we see clear
racial fault lines which divide American society as much now as at
anytime in our past."
</P>
<P>
The NAACP is working with labor groups, women's organizations
and religious leaders to fight a ballot proposal in Washington
State to end affirmative action there, he said.
</P>
<P>
Affirmative action is a practice in the United States that
favors people who are often treated unfairly because of their race
or sex in employment and education.
</P>
<P>
The fight to maintain past gains and to reach economic equity
today is less defined than old-fashioned Jim Crow segregation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"In some important ways," Bond said, "non-white Americans face
problems more difficult to attack than in the years that went
before." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
