<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: China Capable of Playing Bigger Role in Peace Talks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua)-- Since China has important influence
in the Middle East, it is capable of creating a generally cordial
atmosphere in this region, said visiting Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu in an exclusive interview with Xinhua late
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Because of that influence, he said, China could play a bigger
role in the Middle East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, noted for his hard-line stance on the Middle East
peace talks, is in China for a four-day official visit, the first
since he became Israel's prime minister in June of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The 49-year-old prime minister praised China's efforts in
promoting the Middle East peace process, saying that the Chinese
have "goodwill and sympathy" for Israel and the Jewish people.
</P>
<P>
China's stance on the Mideast issue chiefly includes:
</P>
<P>
-- The Mideast peace talks should be based on the United
Nations resolution and comply with the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
-- The agreements already reached should be put into action
conscientiously.
</P>
<P>
-- Terror and violent activities should be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
-- Hostility should be reduced and mutual trust should be
increased.
</P>
<P>
Since the London peace talks between Israel and Palestine
achieved no substantial results and Netanyahu's Washington visit
was fruitless early this month, the peace process was plunged into
a deadlock again.
</P>
<P>
Israel rejected the U.S.-backed proposal for a transfer of 13
percent more land on the West Bank to Palestine, and said that
national security concerns must limit any handover to 9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: China Capable of Playing Bigger Role in Peace Talks (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wiping out violent activities is the important pre-condition
for the peace talks, said Netanyahu, who believes that
"face-to-face and direct" negotiation is still the best way to
break the current deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his belief that the Middle East peace process will
"succeed absolutely," the prime minister promised that Israel will
comply with all the agreements reached, exchange land for security
and for peace, eventually.
</P>
<P>
Within the past two days Netanyahu has held in-depth
discussions with Chinese leaders on breaking the deadlock in
the Mideast peace talks and promoting bilateral relations with
China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese leaders showed much concern about the stalemate in the
Mideast peace process, saying that so long as the peace talks
continue to be stalled, there will be a negative impact on peace
and stability in the region and in the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese leaders expressed their hopes that Israeli leaders
would be farsighted and work with the international community to
break the deadlock in the Mideast peace talks in a positive and
practical manner.
</P>
<P>
They also reiterated that China will, as always, join the
international community to make its due efforts and contribution
to promoting the Middle East peace process
</P>
<P>
Impressed by the knowledge and far-sightedness of Chinese
leaders, Netanyahu said that to develop a relationship with China
is one of the focuses of Israel's foreign policy. It is very
important for the two of the world's oldest people to build a new
partnership in a new era, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
