<HEADLINE> Venezuela: OPEC's Conference to Be Crucial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The ministerial conference of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) will be
crucial to stabilizing the crude prices on international markets,
a Venezuelan official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of Energy and Mines of Venezuela, Erwin Arrieta,
made the remark in an interview with the local media.
</P>
<P>
He said when the conference, planned for June 24, met in
Vienna, Austria, the international energy market would have
perceived the effects of the withdrawal of 1.5 million barrels of
crude per day, which was decided in an agreement on April 1.
</P>
<P>
Arrieta said that the conference would lead to a clear
diagnosis of market behavior at the closing of the second quarter
of the year, which was historically considered the season of less
demand.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that it was still too soon to evaluate the
impact of the agreement between independent producers and the OPEC
which was instituted in Riad on March 21 by Saudi Arabia, Mexico
and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
He said the petroleum ministers of the OPEC as well as
independent producers were constantly in communication to make any
decision which contributed to boosting prices, without discarding
possible additional cuts to the production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
