<HEADLINE> Cuba, Brazil Sign Agreements on Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Cuba and Brazil signed four
agreements on cooperation Wednesday in an effort to bring the two
nations closer together.
</P>
<P>
Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina and his Brazilian
counterpart Luis Felipe Lampreia agreed on a loan that will
provide Havana with 15 million U.S. dollars to buy Brazilian
food. The Cuban foreign ministry said the Brazilian loan could
increase in the future.
</P>
<P>
Robaina and Lampreia also issued a declaration declaring that
the two foreign ministries will work toward establishing a means
of maintaining ongoing exchanges and political consultations.
</P>
<P>
The joint declaration also mentions collaboration on public
health, education, sports, tourism and human rights.
</P>
<P>
The two agreements were followed by an air service agreement,
including an accord on complementary adjustments for technical and
scientific cooperation in tax and customs sectors.
</P>
<P>
Lampreia's three-day trip to Cuba, which ends Wednesday,
contributes positively to improving ties linking Cuba and Latin
America, Robaina said.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreements affirm the desires of both countries to
improve their relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
