<HEADLINE> No Talk of Arms Sales to Brazil, Says Cohen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting United States Defense
Secretary William Cohen says he did not discuss the prospect of
future U.S. arms sales to Brazil at his meeting with Brazilian
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The local media had reported that Cohen's intention was to talk
Brazil into buying U.S. F-16 warplanes during his two-day visit to
Brasilia which started Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Contrary to any press speculation, there was no discussion
about arms," Cohen said soon after meeting Cardoso.
</P>
<P>
He said he discussed with the Brazilian president wide-ranging
issues including difficulties of establishing a defense ministry
in the Brazilian government.
</P>
<P>
Brazil now has four military ministries -- the army, the air
force, the navy and the general staff of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Cohen wrapped up his South American tour later Wednesday, which
also included Chile and Argentina. 
</P>
