<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Gets 780 Million Dollars In Aid Pledges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The international donor community
has pledged financial assistance worth 780 million U.S. dollars to
Sri Lanka for 1998/99, official sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was announced at Sri Lanka's first Development Forum
(formerly known as Aid Group Meeting) which concluded in Paris
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Finance Minister G. L. Peiris who led a Sri Lankan
delegation to the forum said he was happy with the outcome in view
of the extremely difficult environment for global aid, the Finance
Ministry sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources quoted Peiris as saying the donor community's
support was an indication of its confidence in Sri Lanka's
management of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The community provided 700 million dollars for Sri Lanka last
year, the sources said, adding that prior to this year's meeting
Sri Lanka had expected the same amount of assistance for 1998/99.
</P>
<P>
The development forum was attended by Canada, France, Germany,
Italy, Japan, Korea, the Netherlands, Norway, Sweden, Britain and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Also represented were the Asian Development Bank, the
International Finance Corporation, the International Monetary
Fund, Kuwait Fund for Arab Economic Development, the Organization
for Economic Cooperation and Development, Saudi Fund for
Development, the U.N. Development Program and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the World Bank commended the government of Sri
Lanka for its efforts to pursue economic reforms but expressed
concern that prospects were not encouraging for a prompt end to
the 15-year ethnic conflict in the country, the sources added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
