<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Officials from Inland Areas Chosen to Help Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- The second group of 637 officials
have been chosen from across the country to help the Tibet
Autonomous Region and replace the 621 inland officials sent there
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Some officials chosen from Shandong Province and Shanghai have
arrived in Xigaze, the second largest city in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The officials will work for three years in 44 cities or
counties in the region.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the 621 officials in the first group will
leave Tibet before the end of July.
</P>
<P>
According to the third conference on Tibet held in July of
1994, officials would be chosen from central and local government
departments to work for a fixed period in different localities or
sectors in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
In July of 1995, 621 officials from 33 departments of the
central government and from 15 provinces or municipalities arrived
in Tibet to serve as county-level officials.
</P>
<P>
Tibet regional officials said that the first group was an
outstanding contingent of conscientious, pioneering and dedicated
officials who proved popular among Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
The officials chosen from the inland areas have strengthened
prefecture- and county-level leadership in Tibet, cemented ties
between Tibet and other places, promoted the economic growth and
social progress of Tibet and enhanced ethnic unity, according to
regional officials.
</P>
<P>
During the last four years, the gross domestic product of Tibet
has exceeded a 10 percent growth rate, higher than the national
average.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workshop on ASEAN Framework Accord Held in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 28 (Xinhua) -- A training workshop on participation
in the ASEAN Framework Services Agreement is being held here to
enhance the commitment of the grouping's new members.
</P>
<P>
The three-day workshop, which began Wednesday, is jointly
sponsored by the Hanns Seidel Foundation of Singapore and the
ASEAN Secretariat with the cooperation of the Myanmar Foreign
Ministry, the official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The regional workshop is held in Myanmar for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the ASEAN Secretariat, the U.N. Conference on
Trade and Development (UNCTAD) and the World Trade Organization
(WTO) are to give lectures on seven services sectors to be
liberalized within the context of the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA)
such as services of finance, tourism, telecommunications, air and
maritime transport, construction and business.
</P>
<P>
Attending the workshop are core groups from Cambodia, Laos,
Myanmar and Vietnam and experts from the ASEAN Secretariat, UNCTAD
and WTO.
</P>
<P>
According to a decision of the AFTA Council meeting in Kuala
Lumpur last October, the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) is to provide technical assistance to Myanmar and Laos,
its two new members, to help them fulfill their obligations to the
AFTA.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, along with Laos, in July last year joined the ASEAN,
which also includes Brunei, Indonesia, the Philippines, Malaysia,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
