<HEADLINE> Escaped Mafia Boss Extradited to Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Convicted Sicilian Mafia boss Pasquale
Cuntrera was extradited to Italy on Wednesday evening from Spain
where he fled to avoid being sent to prison.
</P>
<P>
Cuntrera, 63, was flown to Rome from Madrid by a military
aircraft on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
He escaped police surveillance in early May just as he was
about to serve a 21-year prison sentence for drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The ailing Mafia boss, who at the time was confined to a
wheelchair, was allowed out of jail on a technicality and
prosecutors were informed of his release too late to order his
re-arrest.
</P>
<P>
Italian police caught up with him while he was out for a stroll
with his wife on the Fuengirola sea-front near Malaga, in Spain.
</P>
<P>
Cuntrera's escape created a storm over the country's justice
system, prompting Justice Minister Giovanni Maria Flick to tender
his resignation last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cuntrera's disappearance coincided with the escape of Licio
Gelli, former grandmaster of the outlawed Propaganda 2 Masonic
Lodge, who fled at the end of April when the Italian Supreme Court
confirmed his 12-year prison sentence for fraudulent bankruptcy in
the 1982 collapse of Banco Ambrosiano. 
</P>
</TEXT>
