<HEADLINE> China to Increase Export of Soda Ash, Caustic Soda, Tires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- China will try to corner a larger
share of the international market for soda ash, caustic ash and
tires, according to a government official in charge of the
petroleum and chemical industry.
</P>
<P>
"Increasing exports is an important means to safeguard the
sustainable growth of China's chemical industry," said Li Yongwu,
director of the State Bureau of Petroleum and Chemical Industry,
during an interview.
</P>
<P>
Although the export of chemical products was affected in the
first quarter of the year by the Asian financial turmoil, Li said,
the proposed target for 1998 exports is realistic.
</P>
<P>
China plans for a 10 percent export growth in the chemical
industry, and to lower the trade deficit of chemical products to
less than 5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The total trade volume for chemical products during the first
quarter was 8.05 billion dollars, including 3.37 billion dollars
of exports, which was 9.2 percent more than the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
To raise the export volume of soda ash, caustic soda and tires
-- the three major export-oriented chemical goods -- related
industry associations and major manufacturers have put forward
specific measures, Li said.
</P>
<P>
China expects to export 120,000 more tons of soda than last
year, and is now stepping up the effort to establish a unified
exporting corporation for soda.
</P>
<P>
China is adopting the practice of the United States, and the
new corporation will embrace eight major soda exporters in
Lianyungang, Tangshan, Weifang, Tianjin and other cities.
</P>
<P>
Experts say a unified export system will help double the export
volume, and the price per ton should rise by 15-to-20 dollars as a
consequence. And China will be more competitive against the United
States, the largest soda producer in the world.
</P>
<P>
China also plans to build docks and storage facilities in
Dalian, Tianjin, Qingdao and Lianyungang dedicated to bulk soda
ash export, and to purchase cargo ships for bulk transportation.
</P>
<P>
China's export volume of soda ash was 600,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
Export of caustic soda this year is expected to be equivalent
to last year, and the bureau is stepping up the building of
unified export bases for the northern and southern part of China,
according to Ye Shangzhen, an official with the bureau.
</P>
<P>
China exported 117,300 tons of liquid caustic soda and 112,300
tons of solid caustic soda in 1997.
</P>
<P>
An organization coordinating unified caustic soda export from
southern China is already operational. It covers the city of
Shanghai and the provinces of Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Anhui and Fujian.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of its counterpart in northern China is under
discussion, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
"The export of tires, especially heavy-duty radial tires, is
promising this year, and supplies of major exporters cannot meet
the demand," Li said.
</P>
<P>
The bureau is committed to place more importance on
coordinating exports in the tire sector, and creating a better
environment for Chinese name brands," he added.
</P>
<P>
China expects to export eight million tires this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Rationally Develop, Utilize Marine Resources (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 28 (Xinhua) -- In the light of the bearing
capacity of marine resources, China has adopted a policy of
developing and utilizing them in a comprehensive way, so as to
promote the coordinated development of the marine industries.
</P>
<P>
The Information Office of the State Council today issued a
white paper titled "The Development of China's Marine Programs",
which said that in recent years China has made constant efforts to
upgrade the maritime fishing, transportation, salt-making and
other traditional industries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China has spared no effort to develop the industry
of marine reproduction and mariculture, offshore oil and gas,
tourism, marine pharmaceuticals and other burgeoning
industries.
</P>
<P>
The country has actively explored new marine resources as far
as possible, and promoted the formation and development of some
potential marine industries, such as deep-water mining,
comprehensive utilization of seawater, and power generation with
marine energy.
</P>
<P>
The white paper said that in 1997 the total output value of the
major marine industries, including ocean fishing, salt-making, the
salt chemicals industry, marine transportation, shipbuilding,
offshore oil and gas, and tourism, topped 300 billion yuan. As a
result, these industries have become forces actively promoting the
development of China's economy as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Since the mid-1980s, China's saltwater aquaculture has
developed rapidly, with a large increase in species and expansion
of breeding areas. The output of such products rose from 1.926
million tons in 1987 to 7.91 million tons in 1997, with their
proportion in the total output of the maritime harvest rising from
27 percent to 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
China attaches great importance to the protection of marine
fisheries resources, and has adopted various measures to conserve
such resources so as to guarantee the implementation of a
sustainable marine development strategy.
</P>
<P>
China has done this by instituting various closed fishing
seasons, closed fishing areas, marine sanctuaries and moratorium
systems, banning harmful fishing gear and methods, and restricting
the size of net meshes and the proportion of young fish.
</P>
<P>
As far back as in the 1960s China began to explore and exploit
offshore oil and gas resources on its own.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s it started to absorb foreign capital and
technology to develop this industry in cooperation with foreign
companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Rationally Develop, Utilize Marine Resources (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By the end of 1997 China had signed 131 contracts and
agreements with 67 oil companies from 18 countries and regions and
imported a total capital of close to six billion US dollars for
this industry.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, more than 100 structures with oil and gas had
been discovered, and 1.7 billion tons of oil reserves and 350
billion cu m of natural gas had been found.
</P>
<P>
Twenty oil and gas fields are under development. With an
offshore oil and natural gas industry in place, in 1997 China's
offshore oil output exceeded 16.29 million tons, and its natural
gas output stood at four billion cu m.
</P>
<P>
China has worked out a policy of utilizing its deep-sea waters
and coastal resources in a rational way.
</P>
<P>
According to the policy, priority shall be given to the
construction of harbors in deepwater coastal areas, and vigorous
efforts will be made to develop marine transportation.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, China's merchant ships had increased to
320,000 with a total deadweight tonnage of close to 50 million.
</P>
<P>
At present, China has 15 harbors each with an annual handling
capacity of more than 10 million tons. In 1997 the volume of
freight handled by the country's major coastal harbors totaled 905
million tons.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the coastal areas have created more than 300
marine and island tourism and recreational zones, with a variety
of marine features.
</P>
<P>
Marine tourism is now a burgeoning industry. In 1997 this
sector received more than 10 million overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
The white paper said that China was one of the world's pioneers
in making salt from seawater. With an area of 430,000 ha, China's
salt pans produced 29.281 million tons of raw salt in 1997. The
major salt chemical products are potassium chloride, bromide,
anhydrous nitre and magnesium chloride.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has listed the exploration and
exploitation of the mineral resources of the Pacific Ocean as a
long-term development project for which it intends to offer
special investment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it has established a special institution in charge
of coordinating and administering China's exploratory and
exploitative activities in the international seabed region.
</P>
<P>
China is the fifth-largest investor in international efforts
for seabed development, and has obtained an exclusive exploration
and development area of 75,000 sq km. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
