<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Warns of Potential Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Several Panamanian rivers have
risen to a dangerous level this week due to the heavy rain, which
is threatening to cause flooding and landslides, a government
official warned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The rainfall, which began this week, has reached six and
one-half inches and will increase in intensity during the coming
days," said Roberto Velasquez, director of the National System for
Civil Protection.
</P>
<P>
He said the first storms so far have taken a severe toll in the
loss of property and human lives. About 100 people have been
killed and two are reportedly missing.
</P>
<P>
International meteorological services predict that Panama will
suffer the worst effects of the El Nino weather phenomenon between
August and December, when sudden climatic changes such as
torrential rains, tornados and floods will strike the nation.
</P>
<P>
Velasquez said that his office has already warned riverside
communities within the country to take preventive measures to
minimize the disasterous effects of El Nino.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of citizens living in high-risk areas will be
relocated to places at least 100 meters from the river, Velasquez
added.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months of this year, Panama was hit by a
serious drought that devastated the country's agriculture and
livestock farms and left two main hydro-electrical plants without
water.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian government worked out emergency plans to fight
the drought. Now, the target will shift to contending with the
floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
