<HEADLINE> Italian PM Promises Increased Investment in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi said here Thursday that his government will try its
best to increase investment in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Prodi made the remarks during the opening ceremony of the first
Italian trade fair in Tirana, the capital city.
</P>
<P>
He said his government is prepared to offer 60 billion lira
(34.8 million U.S. dollars) in emergency aid to Albania. The plan
however has yet to be approved by the Italian parliament.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 Italian companies and enterprises took part in
the fair, which Prodi said is a signal to the industrial and
financial world as well as political circles that Albania enjoys a
healthy investment environment.
</P>
<P>
The fair will help Albania attract more foreign investment, the
Italian prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Italy is Albania's number one trade partner and aid
provider. It also ranks first in the world in terms of investment
in the south-eastern European country.
</P>
<P>
During his one-day stay here, Prodi also met Albanian President
Rexhep Meidani and Prime Minister Fatos Nano. This is the third
visit by Prodi to Albania after the country experienced turmoil in
early 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meidani and Nano expressed appreciation for the Italian
government's support. They also promised to prevent Albanian
refugees from entering Italy illegally. 
</P>
