<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, May 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. scientists said Tuesday that due to global
warming, world-wide glaciers are melting much faster than
scientists had previously thought.
</P>
<P>
According to a study conducted and presented by geologist Mark
Meier and his team at a meeting of the American Geophysical Union
in Boston on Tuesday, "The glaciers are receding and they're
becoming thinner," because of the global warming.
(Glaciers-Melting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Boeing reaffirmed Wednesday that it will
continue to experience delivery delays through this year on new
models of its 737 passenger jets.
</P>
<P>
The Seattle-based airplane manufacturer, in a status report on
its production problems, identified assembly of the newer 737s as
the biggest single problem and the area with the most risk and
uncertainty. But it said the company is making progress in ramping
up the rate of production on the 737, the 747 and other commercial
jetliners. (Boeing-Delivery Delay)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The White House on Wednesday condemned House
Speaker Newt Gingrich for his attack on Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, saying his comment that Albright was an agent
of the Palestinians was "impugning the loyalty" of the secretary
of state.
</P>
<P>
It was the second day that the Clinton administration hit back
at Gingrich. On Tuesday the State Department denounced Gingrich's
comment on Albright as "appalling and outrageous."
(US-Mideast-Gingrich)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl Wednesday gave his firm
backing to his embattled environment minister who faces a call to
resign over recent revelations of contaminated German nuclear
waste shipments.
</P>
<P>
At issue is the disclosure last week that some of Germany's
nuclear waste shipments to French and British reprocessing plants
had leaked much more radiation than official standards permitted.
(Germany-Nuke Row)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. will subsidize 30,000 tons of its barley
for sale to retaliate for Europe's shipment of subsidized grain to
this country, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Use of the Export Enhancement Program (EEP) to help U.S.
growers "is a measured, targeted response to the European Union's
recent sale of heavily subsidized barley into the United States,"
Glickman said. "Our action today demonstrates how seriously we
view the E.U. sale," he added. (US-EU-Barley)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The German cabinet has approved an extension of German
soldiers' peacekeeping mission in Bosnia, a government spokesman
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the Bonn government has also
decided that Germany's contributions to the U.N. peacekeeping
forces in Bosnia, the Stabilization Force (SFOR), will remain at
the current level of 3,000 soldiers. The current mandate of the
35,000 SFOR troops in Bosnia is due to expire on June 19.
(Germany-Bosnia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- France will mobilize 1,000 soldiers to guard airports,
railway stations, sea ports and other places frequented by the
public during the 1998 France Football World Cup finals, announced
the French Interior Ministry Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The mobilization makes up a reinforcement of the Vigipirate
anti-terrorist operation renewed by France since 1995, as the
1,000 soldiers will join 860 of their fellow soldiers already
mobilized over the past three years. (France-World Cup-Security)
</P>
</TEXT>
