<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Province Prepares Against Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan province is
preparing against the worst possible floods in history, with
evacuation and rescue exercises under way throughout the province.
</P>
<P>
Hunan has suffered several floods already this year, with more
rainfall than normal. Experts warn that a flood as big as the
disaster in 1954 might take place this year along the Yangtze
River. The 1954 flood killed more than 33,000 people and caused a
crop loss of 12.5 billion kilos of grain.
</P>
<P>
Government leaders at all levels are demanding frequent
inspections of the anti-flood first line and direct responsibility
for flood-control efforts.
</P>
<P>
Rescue facilities will also be allocated to those local people
in the most dangerous areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Becomes First to Enter Second Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROTENBURG, Germany, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Australia became the
first team to enter the second round at the Women's World
Basketball Championship after beating Germany 88-69 in a group C
match Wednesday in Wuppertal, Germany.
</P>
<P>
The Australians, fourth place finishers at last champoinship,
built a 43-35 halftime lead and played with bench players for most
of the second half.
</P>
<P>
Forward Carla Porter led the team with 13 points, while Annie
La Fleur added 12 and Michelle Griffiths 11.
</P>
<P>
Heike Roth scored a game-high 14 points to lead Germany, who
beat Congo 89-37 in their opening game Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The hosts play Cuba on Thursday, who lost to Australia Tuesday
86-92.
</P>
<P>
Cuba meets Congo later Wednesday to battle for the second place
in the group.
</P>
<P>
A total of 16 teams are divided into four groups in the
preliminaries with the first three of each group advancing into
the second round to be played in Bremen and Berlin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
