<HEADLINE> Birds' World Open to Tourists in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 28 (Xinhua) -- Urbanites in Shanhaiguan Pass,
a tourist zone in north China's Hebei Province, will have an
opportunity for an avian experience at a newly built "birds'
world."
</P>
<P>
The 15,000-square-meter "birds' world" nestled among valleys has
been covered by a 38-meter-high net with an air space of 20,000
cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 rare birds in 70 varieties have been shipped
from southern provinces. They include such wading and
natatorial birds as red-crowned cranes and egrets.
</P>
<P>
Birds fly freely inside the net and sing to visitors who are
allowed to go inside.
</P>
<P>
"We take it for a bird-research-center which combines the
training and protection of birds," said Li Chongwu, general
manager of birds' world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
