<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Calls Parents to Use TV Ratings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore on
Wednesday urged parents to use the TV ratings combined with v-chip
technology to block children's exposure to TV sex and violence, so
as to reduce violent behavior in youngsters.
</P>
<P>
"Of course the recent tragic incidents of children shooting
children give us ever more urgent cause for concern," Gore said
at a news conference on TV ratings survey.
</P>
<P>
"We must explore every option that might help prevent violence
by children and that includes limiting children's exposure to
television violence. To be more specific, helping parents to limit
their own children's exposure to television violence."
</P>
<P>
Gore said, "by the time children complete elementary
school, they will witness more than 8,000 simulated murders and
more than 100,000 simulated acts of violence. By the time the
average child graduates from high school, those numbers double,
and a child will witness almost 20,000 simulated murders, almost
200,000 simulated acts of violence."
</P>
<P>
He said that numerous national experts have demonstrated that
children who do view a large amount of TV violence are
significantly more likely to exhibit aggressive behavior.
</P>
<P>
The vice president said that parents are increasingly
concerned about TV content and more and more of them are
concerned "a great deal" that their children see too much sex
and violence on television.
</P>
<P>
The telephone survey, conducted April 2-26 by Princeton Survey
Research Associates involving 1,358 parents of children ages 2-17,
showed that parents are using TV ratings to help decide what their
children can watch but many can't even name any of the ratings
used for shows.
</P>
<P>
Since October 1, when ABC, CBS, Fox and most cable networks
began using new detailed TV ratings, the letters "V," "S," "L" and
"D" have been showing up on TV screens alongside age-based
ratings, such as "TV-PG" (parental guidance suggested) and "TV-14"
(may be unsuitable for children under 14). The letters stand for
violence, sex, crude language and suggestive dialogue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
