<HEADLINE> Dow Recovers From Slump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial average
reversed its course late this afternoon, recovering much of its
175-point decline as investors sought cheap stocks following a
four-day selloff.
</P>
<P>
At the closing, the Dow was down 27.16 points at 8,939.57. It
was the fourth day of losses for the blue-chip index, which
going into today's session had already lost 208 points since last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The overseas selling spree also hurt the broad market, but
other indicators also bounced back late today.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 was down 2.55 at 1,091.47, and the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index slipped 0.82 at 1,777.27.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-2 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange where volume totaled 681.08 million shares as
against 529.31 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index was down 2.33 at 563.93, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 11.49 at 708.84.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies was down 5.35 at
449.73.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, Hong Kong's Hang Seng stock index plummeted 5.3
percent, Tokyo's Nikkei stock average fell 1.4 percent, and
Indonesia's main index fell 3.9 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
