<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Rises Against Mark, Slips Against yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar Wednesday rose
against the mark, largely affected by the crash of the Russian
stock market.
</P>
<P>
The dollar slipped against the yen. In late New York trading,
the dollar was quoted at 137.40 yen, down from 137.83 late
Tuesday. During New York trading Tuesday, the dollar rose briefly
to a seven-year high against the yen.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also was changing hands at 1.7829 German marks, up
from 1.7705.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that when Russia has economic or political
problems, German currency would show its weakness because of the
close economic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Russian stocks plummeted more than 10 percent Wednesday. The
Russia Trading System is now down more than 50 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The ruble, the nation's currency, recovered from an early fall
Wednesday to ending little changed against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
To protect ruble, the nation's currency, Russia's central bank
raised interest rates from 50 percent to a whopping 150 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday:
1.4711 Swiss francs, down from 1.4717; 5.9740 French francs, up
from 5.9330; 1,755.00 Italian lire, up from 1,743.00; and 1.4564
Canadian dollars, up from 1.4548.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6316 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6367 U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
