<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Drug Being Studied May Prevent Transmission of Herpes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A new study being done at
Seattle-based University of Washington offers hope for millions of
herpes sufferers.
</P>
<P>
The UW virology clinic is one of about 20 sites across the
United States participating in an international two-year study of
the drug called valacyclovir, which may prevent transmission of
genital herpes.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very optimistic," the Seattle Times quoted clinic medical
director Anna Wald as saying. The clinic has studied herpes and
its treatment for two decades.
</P>
<P>
Taking orally every day, after five to seven days it prevents
viral shedding, during which the virus can be transmitted. This
indicates, Wald said, the drug will prevent transmission of the
herpes virus.
</P>
<P>
The new study comes at a time when renewed attention is being
paid to herpes, which over the past decade has been overshadowed
by AIDS. In the United States, about 45 million people -- about
one in very five persons 12 years of age and older -- have genital
herpes. According to a report in the New England Journal of
Medicine, from 1974 to 1992 there was a 30 percent increase in the
disease.
</P>
<P>
The initial outbreak of herpes often results in painful sores
in the genital area. For most, recurrences get milder and less
frequent over the years as the immune system builds up antibodies
to fight the virus. But for babies the virus is devastating,
because their immune systems are not developed. Of babies who get
herpes, a third die and half those who survive suffer permanent
brain damage, Wald said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Orders White House Aides to Testify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A federal judge formally ordered
two presidential aides to tell a grand jury about their
discussions with President Bill Clinton about Monica Lewinsky,
according to court documents released on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson said that a
president's conversations with aides about such a matter can be
covered by the privilege, including those involving first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
But Johnson ruled that even if the conversations are covered by
executive privilege -- the right of a president to get
confidential advice -- Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr had
proven his need for the information was greater.
</P>
<P>
She ordered that presidential aides Bruce Lindsey and Sidney
Blumenthal answer questions they previously refused to answer on
grounds of executive privilege.
</P>
<P>
In her ruling, Johnson concluded that Starr was entitled to the
evidence in part because it "cannot feasibly be obtained
elsewhere."
</P>
<P>
Blumenthal immediately issued a statement saying he would
testify. "If called before the grand jury, I will testify
truthfully and completely to all questions posed to me by Ken
Starr," he said.
</P>
<P>
In its ruling, the court began with the assumption that
Clinton's claim of executive privilege was valid and then weighed
prosecutors' interest in getting the testimony versus the
president's right to confidential advice.
</P>
<P>
The court said that among the conversations covered by
executive privilege were those between the aides and Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff, in a statement, cast the
judge's opinion as a vindication of White House arguments that
conversations with the president -- and among senior advisers,
including the first lady -- are protected by executive privilege.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Warming Causes World Glaciers Melting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists said Tuesday
that due to global warming, world-wide glaciers are melting much
faster than scientists had previously thought.
</P>
<P>
According to a study conducted and presented by geologist Mark
Meier and his team at a meeting of the American Geophysical
Union in Boston on Tuesday, "The glaciers are receding and they're
becoming thinner," because of the global warming.
</P>
<P>
Meier and his team at the University of Colorado at Boulder
looked at characteristics of glaciers worldwide during the last
100 years,and then compared the measurements to today's ice caps.
</P>
<P>
They said glaciers outside of Antarctica and Greenland had
retreated and become thinner and thinner.
</P>
<P>
All of the glaciers in Glacier National Park in Montana will
be gone in the next 50 to 70 years, predicted the U.S. scientists.
</P>
<P>
One of the direct results of the glaciers melting, they said,
would lead to the rising of sea levels which cause beach erosion
and more severe inland storms. And rivers will overflow their
banks more than often.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0350 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
