<HEADLINE> Pakistan Sends Mission to Washington for Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A Pakistani delegation is
expected to arrive in Washington on Friday for talks with U.S.
officials on the South Asian situation following India's five
underground nuclear tests, a U.S. official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will be headed by Senator Akram Zaki, who has
close ties with Prime Minister Mawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's willingness to send the delegation to Washington
was the result of discussions between the Pakistani government
and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott who visited
Islamabad after India's surprise nuclear tests earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
The United States has tried hard to persuade Pakistan not to
follow its arch rival India by conducting the same nuclear tests.
President Bill Clinton has spoken three times by telephone with
Sharif on that issue.
</P>
<P>
U.S. intelligence officials have said Pakistan was nearing
completion of preparations for a nuclear weapon test in a remote
western corner of the country.  
