<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0351 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: E. Africa Pledges to Accomplish Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 27 (Xinhua) -- East African government
officials, who appear satisfied with the donors' promise to
finance the rehabilitation and construction of a multi-billion
dollars road network, have pledged to manage money well so as to
make the ambitious project a success.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was made during a two-day conference in the
northern town of Arusha, where the presidents of Kenya, Uganda
and Tanzania met to ask the donor community to part with 4.664
billion U.S. Dollars to repair or construct 15,273 km of roads in
the region over the next five years to promote regional
integration process.
</P>
<P>
The donor community has promised to grant more than one
billion U.S. Dollars for the first phase of the project, an
amount that has apparently satiated the demands of the three East
African Cooperation (EAC) leaders.
</P>
<P>
The first phase to benefit from the project is the
Mombasa-Malaba-Katuba corridor and Dar es
Salaam-Dodoma-Isaka-Mutukula-Masaka corridor.
</P>
<P>
The executive secretary of the EAC Francis Muthaura said: "A
major leap has been made. We'll make necessary follow-up to make
sure that the roads project is a success."
</P>
<P>
The donor community, he said, has expressed great
understanding and their initial assistance is a great boost to
the development east African nations.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya's Minister for Regional Cooperation, Nicolas Biwott,
was grateful that a start has been made in the roads project,
saying, "the conference has been very fruitful."
</P>
<P>
He said the Western donor countries and multilateral agencies
have respected the desire of the east Africans to have the roads
repaired and built first.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan public works minister, Rebecca Kadaga, the former
foreign minister, said the east African countries are embarking
on a serious project.
</P>
<P>
"We want to put east Africa on the path to prosperity and we
have to start from somewhere," she said. "Roads are very critical
in our context."
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian Minister of Foreign Affairs and International
Cooperation, Jakaya Kikwete, who doubles as the chairman of the
EA Tripartite Commission, said, "the conference has recorded a
major success."
</P>
<P>
"We've been highly honored by the donor community, and we
express our gratitude to them," he said. "This is a good
beginning for an EA integration and development."
</P>
<P>
He allayed fears of some people who doubted whether or not the
government will have transparency in managing the funds for the
road project, noting that "we will make sure every cent will go
for the intended purpose. We should not look back."
</P>
<P>
The remarks came in response to the skeptical attitude held by
some donors who said a history of mismanagement argued against
plowing in more cash.
</P>
<P>
A Western ambassador reportedly said that Kenya and Tanzania
lack the capacity to absorb any huge amount of money for roads.
For instance, he said, "work on the damaged Nairobi-Mombasa road
has not started two years after funding was obtained for that
project from the European Union and the World Bank."
</P>
<P>
Donors further blamed that heavy taxes levied specifically for
road maintenance, like the fuel levy in Kenya and Tanzania,
serviced other ambitious government expenditures or were stolen
from government coffers by officials who often went unpunished.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they said negligence of the Ugandan government
has caused setbacks in repairing a road network which cost 350
million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank representative for Tanzania and Uganda, James
Adams, also said the money offered should be made best use of
with transparency.
</P>
<P>
An aide to Kenya's president, however, said the attendance of
the three heads at the conference reflects the seriousness about
the EA roads project.
</P>
<P>
More than 130 delegates from more than 10 countries and
various leading financial institutions in the world have
participated in the conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
