<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Free Trade Area Achievable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) said Wednesday
that the achievement of a free trade area in the region is not
only realistic but also achievable.
</P>
<P>
Opening the Third Trade and Customs Committee meeting for
COMESA in Lusaka, Enock Kavindele, current chairman for the
Council of Ministers of the 14-member regional body, disclosed
that six member countries have reduced tariffs by 80 percent, two
by 70 percent and three by 60 percent, according to Zambia
National Broadcasting Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
However, Kavindele, also Minister of Commerce, Trade and
Industry, warned that the free trade area would not be achieved
if non-tariff barriers such as the free movement of people and
the right of residence are not removed.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the need to remove barriers in the
transport and communication sector if the free trade area is to
be achieved by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian minister further commended COMESA for involving
the business community and the private sector in the programs of
the regional grouping.
</P>
<P>
Speaking earlier at the meeting, Erastus Mwencha, acting
secretary-general of COMESA, called on member states to adhere to
the timetable for the reduction of tariffs and elimination of
non-tariff barriers.
</P>
<P>
He added that the achievement of a free trade area by the year
2000 is crucial for the regional grouping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980528.0353 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNFPA Hails Brundtland Era at WHO as One of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Population Fund (UNFPA) looks forward to working closely with Dr.
Gro Harlem Brundtland and the World Health Organization (WHO),
particularly in the areas of providing reproductive health and
rights for all, said Dr. Nafis Sadik, Executive Director of UNEPA,
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Brundtland 's nomination for Director General by the WHO
Executive Board was recently endorsed by the World Health Assembly,
WHO's governing body.
</P>
<P>
"Over the years, Dr. Brundtland and I have enjoyed close
cooperation. Dr. Brundtland and I share a particular concern over
the situation of women and girls around the world, especially for
their sexual and reproductive health and rights," said Dr. Sadik.
</P>
<P>
"Her leadership in this area was extraordinary at the
International Conference on Population and Development in Cairo in
1994. The goals and activities of UNFPA are very close in many
ways to those of WHO and I am sure that with the new leadership of
Dr. Brundtland, UNFPA and WHO will continue to work closely and
further strengthen our mutual cooperation," said Dr. Sadik.
</P>
<P>
UNFPA programmes in health, especially in reproductive health,
including adolescent reproductive health, rely on technical
guidance by WHO, said Dr. Sadik. In addition to funding many joint
programmes on reproductive health, UNFPA collaborates closely with
WHO and other United Nations agencies on the Safe Motherhood
Initiative, the Joint Programme on HIV/AIDS, and the campaign to
eliminate female genital multilation.
</P>
<P>
UNFPA is the world's largest internationally funded source of
population assistance to developing countries. It supports efforts
to improve reproductive health and family planning services on the
basis of individual choice, and to formulate population policies
in support of efforts towards sustainable development and
population stability.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
