<HEADLINE> Europe Faces Soil Erosion: FAO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 27 (Xinhua) -- About 220 million hectares
of land in Europe are being degraded, equaling an area four times
the size of France, the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization
(FAO) said.
</P>
<P>
This is due to destruction of forests, excessive use of
fertilizers, manure and pesticides, inappropriate tillage
practices, monoculture and excessive grazing pressure, according
to a FAO press release distributed by the U.N. Department of
Public Information here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A regional FAO project is currently mapping soil and terrain
vulnerability in Central and Eastern Europe while European nations
are discussing the harmonization of soil data and soil maps.
</P>
<P>
The FAO sees harmonized soil data for the whole of Europe as a
way toward a common basis for policy decisions related to land
use, land management and environmental protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
