<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Business to Hire More Welfare Recipients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said
on Wednesday the federal government is doing its part by hiring
people off the welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
At a White House event marking the first anniversary of his
"Welfare-to-Work Partnership" initiative, Clinton called on private
firms to follow suit, urging businesses to double their welfare
hires this year.
</P>
<P>
Five thousand companies taking part in the "Welfare to Work
Partnership" hired 135,000 welfare recipients in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the federal government is well on the way to
meeting its goal of hiring 10,000 people from welfare by the year
2000. Since March 1997, federal agencies and departments have
hired 4,811 welfare workers, or 45 percent of the objective.
</P>
<P>
The White House has hired seven welfare recipients for clerical
and support work.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said welfare caseloads have fallen to 8.9 million, a
drop of 3.3 million since he signed the welfare reform law two in
the fall of 1996. The percentage of Americans on welfare is at its
lowest level since 1969 -- 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The new law, requiring people to leave the welfare rolls in a
maximum of five years and to work after two years, puts states
under increasing pressure to move people into jobs.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, the president has kept calling on the private
sector to hire welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
The 5,000 companies participating in the partnership are each
committed to hiring at least one person. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
