<HEADLINE> White House Says Gingrich Remarks on Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The White House on Wednesday
condemned House Speaker Newt Gingrich for his attack on
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, saying his comment that
Albright was an agent of the Palestinians was "impugning the
loyalty" of the secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
It was the second day that the Clinton administration hit back
at Gingrich. On Tuesday the State Department denounced
Gingrich's comment on Albright as "appalling and outrageous."
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, Gingrich accused the Clinton administration of
pressuring Israel on the issue of withdrawal from the West Bank.
He said: "I think it's wrong for the American secretary of State
to become the agent of the Palestinians."
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said Gingrich's remarks
were "wholly inappropriate."
</P>
<P>
"I think it was clear that he was impugning the loyalty of
the secretary of state and that was most unfortunate," McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich has been visiting Israel since last week along with
other members of Congress from both parties. He made public
support to Israel's position on the Middle East peace process
during his visit.
</P>
<P>
He said he supported Jerusalem as the "eternal" and "united"
capital of Israel, even though Palestinians view it as the
capital of a future state.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said the speaker was just making "provocative
statements that appear to side with one party against another
party."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
