<HEADLINE> Boeing Continues 737 Delivery Delays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Boeing reaffirmed Wednesday
that it will continue to experience delivery delays through this
year on new models of its 737 passenger jets.
</P>
<P>
The Seattle-based airplane manufacturer, in a status report on
its production problems, identified assembly of the newer 737s as
the biggest single problem and the area with the most risk and
uncertainty. But it said the company is making progress in ramping
up the rate of production on the 737, the 747 and other commercial
jetliners.
</P>
<P>
Boeing posted a loss of 178 million U.S. dollars last year as
the cost of fixing its production problems overwhelmed its
earnings. Since last fall, the financial world has monitored
closely Boeing's efforts to get its production on track, which
also have been a source of mounting concern on Wall Street. So
far, the production problem has cost the company more than 2
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Today's report indicates that Boeing has a long way to go to
get back to normal production, although it said it still expects
to meet its goal of delivering 250 commercial jets in the first
half this year. Boeing so far has delivered 180.
</P>
<P>
As of today, Boeing has delivered 33 of the newer-model 737s.
The company said the delay in the program is being caused by parts
shortages, out-of-sequence work and design changes needed to meet
U.S. and European certification requirements.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Boeing's 747 assembly line is increasing production
from four to five airplanes a month. But the question is how long
that new rate can be sustained if Asian carriers begin delaying or
canceling deliveries. The company said that most of the airlines
in Asia are taking delivery of their 1998 airplanes, but it
doesn't know what will happen next year. Boeing has indicated that
as many as 60 airplanes already ordered by Asian airlines could be
at risk of delay or cancellation over the next three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
